{ The young Kasparov liked playing positions with a ‘small center’, so he coordinated his opening choice around this. Here follow two nice examples from the eighties: }
1. d5
{ This thematic break underlies much of White's play in this type of position. }
1... exd5 2. e5 Qe6 3. Nd4
{ 19.Rad1  would probably have been better, e.g.  Nc4  20.Bc1  Rc7  21.Nd4  and White indeed gets a dangerous initiative after  Qc8  22.Nf5  . }
3... Qxe5 4. Nf5 Bf6
{ So far Black has defended himself in exemplary fashion.  Also, after   20...Nc4 !?  White had planned  21.Qf1  with the idea of Bd4.  Therefore, on the previous move White should prefer   21.Qh5 !?  g6  22.Bd4  Qxd4  23.Nxd4  gxh5  24.Rxe7  and White has enough compensation for his pawn.  He could also choose to win the pawn back through   21.Bxb6  , but now the queens are exchanged:  Qxe2  22.Rxe2  Bf6  23.Bd4  with an equal game.  The engine however suggests the reply  21...Bd6 !  ! with a huge advantage for Black.  Note that   20...g6 ?  fails to  21.Bd4 !  Qxe2  22.Nh6#  .  And on   20...Bc5 ?  White wins after  21.Qh5 !  Rfe8  22.Ne7+ !  +-  . }
5. Qg4 Rce8
{ Also not great would have been:   21...Rfe8 ?!  22.Bd2  Qxa1  23.Rxa1  Bxa1  24.h4 !  ↑  but with   21...Qc3 !  Black could have held his position:  22.Ne7+ !  Bxe7  23.Bd4  Qxd4  24.Qxd4  Bf6  25.Qg4  Bxa1  26.Rxa1  +=  and Black has survived. }
6. Bd2 Qxa1
{ This loses immediately,  but Najdorf would also have gone down after   22...Qc7  23.Nh6+  Kh8  24.Rxe8  Rxe8  25.Qf5 !  Re4  26.Bxe4  dxe4  27.Rc1  Nc4  28.Bg5  +-  winning.  Relatively better is   22...Qb2  , but White will also now have a clear advantage after  23.Nh6+  Kh8  24.Qh5  , after which  Re4  is forced. Then  25.Bxe4  dxe4  26.Bb4  is no picnic, although Black is still in the game after  e3 !? }
7. Rxa1 Bxa1 8. Nxg7 Bxg7
{ 24...Bc8  25.Ne6+  Kh8  26.Qf5  +-  and mate follows. } 9. Bh6 *

