1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d5 5. Bg5 Ne4 6. cxd5 Nxg5 7. Nxg5 e6 8.
Nf3 exd5 9. e3 O-O 10. Bd3 Nc6 11. O-O Ne7 12. b4 Bf5
{ This looks like a small success for Black, but in practice this bishop will soon be very much missed.  Better is   12...Bg4  . }
13. Bxf5 Nxf5 14. b5 Qd6 15. Qb3 Ne7 16. Rfc1 Kh8
{ Probably   16...Rfc8  should have been preferred. } 17. Rc2 h6 18. Rac1 c6
{ Black will have to do this sooner or later as the pawns on c7 and d5 are both potential targets. But now White's minority attack is almost complete. }
19. Na4
{ Petrosian is not in a hurry to take on c6. He rather brings a knight to c5 first.  At this moment   19.bxc6  doesn't do any harm, but after  bxc6  20.Na4  Black does have the option of playing  Rfb8  immediately, which gives him some chances of counterplay. }
19... Rab8 20. g3 Kh7 21. Nc5 Rfd8 22. bxc6
{ Now the former world champion does not see any more improving moves to play before the trade. }
22... bxc6 23. Qa4 Qf6 { This gives White a shortcut. } 24. Kg2
{ White continues to play steadily,  but   24.Ne5 !  would already have presented Black with insurmountable problems. }
24... Ra8 25. Nb7
{ White focuses his attention on the weak pawn on c6.  Doubling rooks on the b-file with   25.Rb2  was also fine, though less convincing. }
25... Re8 26. Na5 g5 { Black desperately tries to get some counterplay going. }
27. h3 { There was nothing wrong with the immediate   27.Nxc6  either. } 27...
Qf5 28. Nxc6 { The pawn has been rounded up in 4 short moves ! } 28... Qe4 29.
Rc5 f5 30. Qc2 Nxc6 31. Rxc6 f4
{ Black tries to create some chaos. However, as is common in bad positions, he succeeds only in weakening his own king. }
32. exf4 gxf4 33. g4
{ White keeps all the lines leading to his king closed. In the final conversion phase, he proceeds to take advantage of the Black king's vulnerable position. }
33... Bxd4 34. Qd2 Bg7 35. Re1 Qa4 36. Qxd5
{ Behold the difference between both king's positions. It's clear Black's king does not have much time left. }
36... Rxe1 37. Nxe1 Rf8 38. Nf3 Kh8 39. Rc7 a6 40. Qb7 Rg8 41. Nh4
{ Black resigned in view of   41.Nh4  Qd4  42.Ng6+  Kh7  43.Ne7  Rb8 !?  44.Qc6 !  when the threat of Nf5 is deadly. }
*

