[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Pawn Structures and Practical Examples"]
[Black "Lobron, E. vs. Beim, V."]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 c6 3. Bg5 h6 4. Bh4 Bf5 5. e3 Nd7 6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 Ngf6 8.
O-O e6 9. c4 Be7 10. Nc3 O-O 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Rab1 a5 13. a3 Re8 14. Bxf6 Bxf6
15. Qc2 Nb6 16. Na4
{ Perhaps White should have preferred   16.b3  or   16.Nd2  , but then he would be hard pressed to find a meaningful plan. }
16... Nc4
{ Black has succeeded in stationing a knight on c4. The question is whether it can stay there. }
17. Nc5 b6 18. Nd3 a4
{ With this move and the next, Black stabilizes his knight's position, which means he must have an advantage. }
19. Nd2 b5
{ So, the knight on c4 will stay there. White will be unable to put pressure on the c6-pawn. }
20. Rbe1
{ Since the minority attack will come to nothing, White tries another tack: he aims to push e3-e4 through. }
20... Qa5 21. Nb1 Be7 22. Nc3 b4 { Black refuses to rest on his laurels. } 23.
axb4 Bxb4 { With the tactical threat ...Nxb2. } 24. Rc1 Bxc3 25. Qxc3
{ White doesn't want to play   25.bxc3  because then Black would have gotten a very dangerous passed pawn, but this continuation would still, comparatively speaking, have been better. }
25... Reb8 { The b2-pawn has become even more vulnerable. } 26. Qxa5 Rxa5 27.
Rc2 Rb3 28. Rd1 { So far Beim has played an excellent game. } 28... Rab5
{ Black just continues maneuvering and with his last move he'll seize a pawn.  The funny thing is Black could have capitalised even faster. He would be able to make direct use of his passed pawn after the unexpected though thematic   28...Nxb2 !  This works as follows:  29.Nxb2   29.Rxb2  Rxb2  30.Nxb2  a3  31.Nd3  a2  32.Ra1  and now  Rb5  will decide.  29...a3  30.Nd3  a2  . White has to give up a rook, after which the matter is settled. }
29. Kf1 Nxb2 30. Nxb2 Rxb2 31. Rxb2 Rxb2
{ Now Black still has some technical work to do to win the rook endgame. } 32.
Ra1 Rb4 33. Ke2 h5 34. h4 Kh7 35. Ra2 Kg6 36. Kd3 Kf5 37. Kc3
{ White can't prevent Black's king entering somewhere.   37.f3  Rb3+  38.Kd2  a3  would also have been hopeless for White. }
37... Rc4+ 38. Kd3 Kg4 39. g3 f5
{ An accurate move, eliminating the option of e3-e4. } 40. Ke2 Rb4 41. Ra3
{ White is in zugzwang. } 41... Rb2+ 42. Kf1 Kf3 { Strong endgame technique ! }
43. e4+ Rb3 { White resigned. } *

