1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. cxd5 exd5 4. Nc3 c6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Bg5 Bf5 7. e3 Nbd7 8.
Bd3 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Bd6 10. O-O O-O 11. Rab1 a5 12. Ne2 Qe7 13. Bf4 Ne4 14. Bxd6
Nxd6
{ The knight has reached the nice square d6. From here it controls the important squares e4 and c4. }
15. Nd2 f5
{ The right continuation. Black's pieces are lined up well enough to justify this move, which is nonetheless committal. When Black plays f5 he should bear in mind that the e5-square becomes weaker. }
16. Rbe1
{ White intends with f2-f3 to play e3-e4, but Black keeps this aspect of the game under tight control. }
16... Rf6 17. Nc3 g5 18. Re2 Re6 19. Rfe1 Re8 20. f3 Nf6
{ Black has set up his attack so solidly that White has no chance of becoming active. }
21. Kh1 Kh8 22. Kg1 { It's clear White doesn't know which way to turn. } 22...
Qf7 23. Nb3
{ Perhaps   23.Na4  could be tried, but even so, after  g4  24.Nc5  R6e7  Black has a splendid position. }
23... b6 24. Nd2
{ After some preparations Black continues trying to force weaknesses in White's camp. }
24... g4 25. Kh1 Qh5 26. e4
{ Panic, although White's position was already decidedly non-trivial to play. }
26... gxf3 27. gxf3 fxe4 28. fxe4 dxe4 29. Qg3
{ The position is nearly hopeless for White. } 29... Nf5 30. Qc7 e3 31. Nf1
Qf3+ 32. Rg2 R6e7
{ 32...Ng4  was even stronger, but Black is winning regardless. } *

