1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Nbd7 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 Be7 7. e3 O-O 8.
Qc2 Re8 9. Bd3 c6 10. h3 Nf8 11. O-O g6 12. Rab1 Ne6 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. b4 a6
15. a4 Qd6 16. Rfc1 Bd7 17. b5
{ White decides to play his minority attack at once. But are his pieces ideally placed for this yet ? }
17... axb5 18. axb5 c5 { Kasparov reacts in principled fashion. } 19. dxc5 Nxc5
{ Black's pieces have suddenly become very active. And there also happens to be a tactical threat that White overlooked. }
20. Rd1
{ This loses the exchange.  The only move was   20.e4  , although Black also here could obtain an advantage after  Nxd3  21.Qxd3  Bxc3  22.Qxc3  dxe4  when he's a pawn up. }
20... Bxc3 21. Qxc3 Nxd3 22. Rxd3 Bf5 23. Rbd1 Bxd3 24. Qxd3
{ This position is technically won and the former world champion managed to prove this, although the technique left something to be desired. }
24... Rec8 25. h4 Ra3 26. Qd4
{ After   26.Qxd5  Black intended  Qxd5  27.Rxd5  Ra1+  28.Kh2  Ra2  and Rcc2. }
26... Rac3 27. g3 Rc1 28. Rxc1 Rxc1+ 29. Kg2 b6 30. h5 Rc4 31. Qd3 Qe6 32. h6
Qe4
{ Not the most practical.  It would have been better to admit having made a mistake and play   32...Qd6  . }
33. Qa3 Rc8 34. Qa1
{ With   34.Qa6 !  Akopian could have given Black pause for thought:  Re8  35.Qxb6  . }
34... d4 { Well found. } 35. exd4 Qd5 36. Qe1 g5 37. g4 Kf8 38. Qb4+ Ke8 39.
Kg3 f6 40. Qb1 Rc7 41. Qa1 Kf7 42. Qb1 Ke6
{ Black has observed he needs to let his king take part in the game, but of course this entails risks. Kasparov makes his king walk across half the board until it finally finds a safe shelter. }
43. Qe1+ Kd7 44. Qb1 Kc8 45. Qe1 Qd6+ 46. Kg2 Re7 47. Qc1+ Kb8
{ The king is now safe and the game is over. } 48. Qc2 Qd5 49. Qc3 Qxb5
{ 49...Re4 !  would have ended things at once. } 50. Qa3 Qd7 51. Qb4 Qxg4+
{ And now White acknowledged defeat. } *

