1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Nbd7 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 Be7 7. e3 O-O 8.
Bd3 Re8 9. Qc2 Nf8 10. O-O c6 11. h3 g6 12. Rab1 Ne6 13. Bh6 Ng7 14. b4 a6 15.
a4 Bf5 { This bishop trade represents a first small success for Black. } 16.
Ne5 Rc8 17. Bxg7 Bxd3 18. Nxd3 Kxg7 19. Rb3 Bd6 20. b5
{ White's impulsive push is poorly timed. Black responds in the correct manner. }
20... cxb5 21. axb5 a5
{ In this way he will create a protected passed pawn on the a-file. White's pieces aren't stationed well enough to take advantage of the c-file. As a matter of fact: it's Black who lays hands on this file. }
22. Qb2
{ It's possible he had planned   22.b6 ?  in order to prevent Black from having a protected passed pawn and found out now that this plan falls into pieces. Black would respond with the strong  Ne4 !  23.Qb2  Nxc3  24.Rxc3  Rxc3  25.Qxc3  Qxb6  winning a pawn. }
22... b6
{ Black gets his way: he has a protected passed pawn and it remains unclear how White can make a stand on the c-file. At the same time a knight can't even jump to c6. }
23. Na4 Rc4 24. Ra1 Ne4
{ Black makes optimal use of the outposts protected by the d5-pawn. } 25. f3
{ An undesirable weakening of Whites own pawn structure. } 25... Ng3 26. Ne5
Bxe5 { Of course Black doesn't allow the knight to get to c6. } 27. dxe5 Qc7
28. Kh2 Nf5 29. f4 Rc2
{ It's clear Black has a big advantage. Gelfand tries to turn the tide in a tactical manner, but this will only backfire. }
30. Rc3 Qxc3 31. Qxc3 Rxc3 32. Nxc3 Nxe3 33. Na4
{ Ivanchuk continues playing with relentless competence and skill, making use of his very strong passed pawn. }
33... d4 34. Ra3
{ 34.Nxb6  Rb8  35.Nd7  Rxb5  is also completely lost for White. } 34... Nc4
35. Rd3 Rd8 36. Kg3 Rd5 37. Kf2 g5
{ The inclusion of Black's king seals the deal. } 38. g3 Kg6 *

