[Black "Counterplay on the kingside with a Black pawn on e4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2b1r3/1p3ppp/p1pb4/8/PP1Pp3/4P3/3N1PPP/6K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ As the pawn structure in the beginning already has shown, square e4 can be a good outpost for a black knight. However, White can often trade this piece off, which typically results in Black recapturing with the d-pawn and driving away any White pieces from f3 or d3.    As those were useful defensive squares for White, Black could take this as a signal to attack. In the development of his attack, he might deploy a rook lift to the sixth rank, perhaps also supported by the light-square bishop and possibly even the queen and the remaining knight. This adds up to adequate material for an attack on White’s king.  Practice shows Black oftentimes succeeding in amassing such attacking forces, but also indicates that White’s king’s position is very solid and possesses numerous defensive resources. A good fight is guaranteed! }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Pawn Structures and Practical Examples"]
[Black "Song, J. vs. Grachev, B."]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 Nf6 4. Bg5 Nbd7 5. e3 Be7 6. Nc3 O-O 7. Rc1 a6 8. cxd5
exd5 9. Bd3 c6 10. Qc2 Re8 11. O-O Nf8 12. h3 Ne4
{ Black tries to free his game with this thematic idea. } 13. Bxe7 Qxe7
{ The knight on e4 dominates much of the position and therefore White usually does best to trade it. }
14. Bxe4 dxe4 15. Nd2
{ The normal reaction.   15.Ne5  is also plausible. Behind this move lies a subtle idea: if Black wants to chase away the knight by playing  f6  , he'll block the sixth rank, which he wanted to use, for instance with a rook lift to g6 via e6. Now, however, the pawn on f6 would be in the way. A further advance with...f6-f5 is possible, but makes Black's bishop worse and runs the risk of a triumphal return to e5 by a White knight. }
15... Bf5
{ Black prefers to do without   15...f5  for the above-mentioned reasons. } 16.
f4
{ Black's last move had, however, a tactical drawback: this pawn can't be taken en passant due to the diagonal pin. }
16... Rad8 17. Ne2 { Probably somewhat better is   17.Nc4  . } 17... Ng6 18.
Qc5 Qf6
{ Of course Black avoids trading queens.  Black could also have prepared a piece sacrifice with   18...Qe6  . }
19. Qb6
{ White now could have played   19.g4  Bc8  20.Qh5  after which his defences appear to hold firm. }
19... Bc8 20. Rc5 h6 21. Nc4 Ne7 22. Nc3 Qg6
{ It seems Black is on the back foot, but in fact, with his last move he has just completed a regrouping that is highly aggressive in nature. }
23. Kh2 { 23.Ne5  Qg3  would be good for Black. } 23... f6
{ Not only to eliminate Ne5 as an option, but also to protect the g5-square one more time so that Black can start the advance of the h-pawn. }
24. Rd1 h5 { This was Black's intention. } 25. d5
{ White sees the storm coming and makes a bid for activity.  Passive defence, however, was better:   25.Re1  h4  26.Re2  Qg3+  27.Kh1  and even though this looks risky, Black has nothing decisive. }
25... Nf5 { The knight is joining the battle. } 26. Ne2
{ In order to protect the g3-square, but now Black gains the upper hand. }
26... Be6
{ Trying to make use of the pin on the d-file.  Grachev, however, had at his disposal:   26...Nh4 !  and after  27.Rg1  there would appear the nice combination:  Nf3+ !!  28.gxf3  Qf5  29.Rg3  h4  30.Rg4  exf3  31.Nd4  Qd3 !  and the defences of White's king are melting away. }
27. d6 Rd7
{ Black leaves nothing to chance. He keeps b7 protected so that the queenside counterplay doesn't progress too far. }
28. Qb4 Red8 29. Qc3 b5
{ This doesn't quite suit the situation.   29...Kh7  would have been a good continuation after which Black is clearly better. }
30. Nb6
{ Luckily for Grachev, White misses his chance.  White could have defended himself adequately with the exchange sacrifice   30.Rxf5 !?  There follows  Qxf5  31.Nd4  Qd5  32.Nb6  Qxd6  33.Nxd7  Rxd7  with a tough struggle. }
30... Rxd6 31. Rxd6 Rxd6 32. Rxc6
{ After White's natural moves there appears the twist: } 32... Nxe3 33. Ng3
{ 33.Qxe3  Rxc6  would be curtains too. } 33... h4 { White resigned. } *

