{ Please click on the forward arrow button. The diagram will show a visual representation of the ideas mentioned below.  After having seen the previous example, the most obvious question would be whether Black can perform the same ideas without the pawn recapture on e4 or even, perhaps, the immediate rook lift. This idea doesn’t sound that stupid, since the Black pieces have a fair amount of scope to roam on the kingside. When looking at games, this scenario regularly occurs and if Black succeeds in mobilising his reserves, White could face a tough struggle.     One of these reserves is in fact not a queenside piece but rather the h-pawn! It can be pushed forward to help in the attack. A pattern that can sometimes occur is for example when Black has a rook on g6 facing White’s king on g1. The pawn then already is on h4. With ...Bc8-h3 he’ll force White to answer Be2-f1.   And now suddenly ...Bh3xg2 is possible due to Bf1xg2 and h4-h3. Such attacking ideas are important to note, to provide detail and shape for a practical player’s attacking ideas. }
