1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 c6 7. Bd3 Nbd7 8.
Nf3 O-O 9. O-O Re8 10. Qc2 Nf8 11. h3 Be6 12. Bf4 Bd6 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. a3 Qe7
15. b4 Rac8 16. Rfc1 N6d7 17. Ne2 Ng6 18. Ng3 Ndf8 19. Nd2
{ Since White's minority attack has been on the back burner for some time, Black transfers some pieces towards the White king's position. There White has already played the weakening move h2-h3; this pawn can become a target. }
19... Nh4 20. Nb3 Qg5 21. Kh2 Rc7
{ This is instructive. Black wants to preserve his bishop for the attack and for this reason he creates a retreat square on c8. }
22. Nc5
{ Maybe   22.b5  makes more sense here, because the reply to the text is so self-evident. }
22... Bc8 23. Re1
{ A different way of bracing himself against the coming storm was   23.Qd1  This threatens to disturb the black plan by means of Qh5, and after  g6  24.Qf1  the defences look quite solid. }
23... g6 24. Rac1 h5 25. b5
{ Karpov underestimates the danger.  But even after the superior   25.e4  his counterplay would have arrived a bit late, since the 'little combination' from the game still works. }
25... Nxg2
{ Black's initiative is very strong. This cute little tactic opens lines within and through White's kingside structure. }
26. Kxg2 h4 27. bxc6 { 27.e4 ?  doesn't work on account of  b6  28.Nb3  Ne6 ! }
27... hxg3 28. fxg3 Rxe3
{ Black doesn't take back on c6 'automatically', but instead continues to further weaken the White king's position.  After   28...Rxc6  29.Bb5  White would have the upper hand. }
29. Rxe3 Qxe3 30. cxb7 Bxb7
{ A difficult moment for White: his king is unsafe and the remaining central pawn is hanging. }
31. Qc3
{ After   31.Qb2  there would follow  Ne6 !  and Black stands better. But this move allows Black a significant tactical chance to do even more damage. }
31... Rxc5 { Well found by the Ukranian. } 32. Qxc5 { 32.dxc5 ??  d4+ } 32...
Qxd3 { Black has two pieces for the rook, which gives him a winning position. }
33. Qc3 Qe2+ 34. Kg1 Ne6 { The pieces need to be brought into the attack. } 35.
Re1 Nxd4 36. Kh1 Nb5 { By now Karpov had seen enough. } *

