1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nc3 c6 6. Bg5 Be7 7. Qc2 g6 8. e3
Bf5 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nbd7 11. Bh6 Ng4 12. Bf4 O-O 13. O-O Re8 14. h3 Ngf6
15. Ne5 Nb6 16. Bg5 Ne4 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 18. Qc2 Nd6 19. Na4 Nbc4 20. Nxc4 Nxc4
21. Nc5 Nd6 22. Rac1
{ It can sometimes be hard to come up with a sound plan. In this case Black opts for a mixture of the standard plans, trusting his experience to stick them together at a later date. }
22... Qg5
{ Black tries to prepare an attack on the kingside by moving forward pawns on that side of the board. White struggles to develop any counterplay, because his minority attack doesn't get off the ground. }
23. Qd1 h5 24. Kh1 Re7
{ A useful move. The rook is protecting b7 so that the knight can be freed up; at the same time though, the rook might be useful on other 7th rank squares. }
25. Nd3 Ne4 26. Nc5 Nd6 27. Nd3 Qf5
{ Black's queen makes way for the strategically desirable g5-g4 push. } 28. Ne5
f6 29. Nf3 Rg7
{ Somewhat too early would be   29...g5  because of  30.Qc2  - when Black doesn't want to trade queens, but may have to because the check on g6 is annoying. }
30. Nh2 Re8 31. Kg1 Ne4 32. Qf3 Qe6 33. Rfd1 g5
{ A crucial moment. Black decides to set in motion a pawn storm in front of his own king. The move implies a pawn sacrifice deserving accurate calculation. }
34. Qxh5 f5
{ This will make the advance ...g5-g4 possible again. The minority attack is in full swing. }
35. Re1
{ If the queen retreats with   35.Qe2  there would follow  g4  36.hxg4  fxg4  and the open files against White's king will ensure Black a strong initiative. }
35... g4 { But now the White queen is in grave danger. } 36. hxg4 fxg4 37. f3
{ After this mistake things will end swiftly.   37.Qh4  Qd6 !  would, however, also give Black a winning advantage. For instance:  38.Nxg4  Or   38.Nf1  Qe6 !  and the threat ...Rh7 can only be met by  39.Nh2  but now  Rf8  40.Rc2  Rf6  followed by ...Rh6 wins.  38...Rh7  winning a piece. }
37... gxf3 38. Nxf3
{ White's queen is now in serious trouble, and Black ends the game in a sophisticated fashion.  After the alternative   38.Qxf3  Black would have played  Rf8  39.Qe2  Ng3  40.Qd3  Qh6  and gone for a mate motif instead. There is no answer to the battery being set up along the h-file. }
38... Rh7 39. Qe5 Qc8 40. Qf4 Rf8 41. Qe5 Rf5
{ Her Majesty is trapped ! White resigned. } *

