{ Please click on the forward arrow button. The diagram will show a visual representation of the ideas mentioned below.  @@HeaderStart@@Plan B: Central Play@@HeaderEnd@@An important plan of playing is to focus all attention on the center. White has the possibility of constructing a strong pawn center, which can come into being if he manages to follow up e3-e4 after f2-f3.   Usually, this plan is only carried out in a proper manner if White has his king’s knight to e2 and not to f3. This is different from what we’ve implied so far, but can occur in the Queen’s Gambit, to say nothing of certain lines within the Nimzo-Indian.    After Black exchanges on e4, White forms a ‘front’ with adjacent pawns on d4 and e4 side by side, which then need to not be vulnerable to immediate attack.  For White it’s also important to think about exactly if and how he will be able to move these pawns further: after either d4-d5 or e4-e5 a crucial central square would fall into his opponent’s hands.   Yet there are countless examples in which White manages e4-e5 in particular. Schematically, the push could look like this:    The Black knight  (which is mostly playing a defensive role)  is chased away, and if White after ...Nf6-d5 avoids the exchange by playing Nc3-e4, there will be a strong chance of violent kingside action developing at the drop of a hat. Two former world champions, Mikhail Botvinnik and his pupil Garry Kasparov, saw the benefits of White’s setup; hence good examples of it, where they succeeded in executing White’s plan in a successful manner, can be found in their play.   Nevertheless we should not forget that these features of White’s plan can be double-edged. If Black gains control of important central squares and manages to set up a solid blockade, it may prove possible to not only nip White’s initiative in the bud, but also even play to win, thanks to Black’s static advantages. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Pawn Structures and Practical Examples"]
[Black "Botvinnik, M. vs. Keres, P."]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd3 Nbd7 8.
Qc2 Re8 9. Nge2
{ The knight doesn't go to its natural square f3. White aims to prepare the e4 thrust by means of first this, and then f2-f3. }
9... Nf8 10. O-O c6 11. Rab1
{ It is questionable whether this fits with the above-mentioned plan.  More consistent would be   11.Rae1  . }
11... Bd6 12. Kh1 Ng6 13. f3 Be7
{ Worse is   13...h6  14.Bxf6  Qxf6  15.e4  and Black has almost already been overrun. }
14. Rbe1 Nd7 15. Bxe7 Rxe7 16. Ng3 Nf6 17. Qf2 Be6
{ This careless move could already have gotten Black into big trouble.  Perhaps he had to play   17...Kh8  to anticipate White's possible advances, keeping options open against pushes of either the e- or f-pawn. }
18. Nf5
{ Probably much stronger here would have been   18.f4 !  . A possible continuation then is:  Nf8  19.f5  Bd7  20.e4  dxe4  21.Ncxe4  and things could have ended disastrously for him. }
18... Bxf5 19. Bxf5 Qb6
{ After having prepared it carefully, Botvinnik now launches the central attack. }
20. e4 dxe4 21. fxe4 Rd8 22. e5
{ In principle, the pawns stand better next to one other. With this move, White gives away squares in the center which the black knights can use. Botvinnik, however, had seen that this move secures him an outpost on d6, which will be useful for a knight in future. }
22... Nd5
{ 22...Ne8  is very passive but at least it defends against the above-mentioned positional threat. }
23. Ne4 Nf8 24. Nd6 Qc7 25. Be4 Ne6
{ It seems Black has everything under control, but this will turn out to not be strictly true. With his next move White forces concessions.  The best chance of salvation was   25...Rxd6  26.exd6  Qxd6  but White would still have a large advantage after  27.Bxd5  cxd5  28.Rxe7  Qxe7  29.Qf5 }
26. Qh4 g6
{ This is a huge weakening of the king's position, but what else could Black do ?  A: After   26...Nf8  first the positionally desirable  27.Bxd5  cxd5  is played  (as in the game)  , and only then the direct attack comes:  28.Nf5  Re6  29.Qg5  Ng6  30.h4  with annoying pressure.  B:   26...h6  is no fun either after  27.Nf5  . }
27. Bxd5 cxd5 28. Rc1
{ The knight on d6 is doing an excellent job. It not only prevents counterplay along the c-file, but it's also attacking 'pressure points' in Black's camp. }
28... Qd7 29. Rc3
{ And so the rook is transferred to the h-file along the 3rd rank, much as we all learned as beginners }
29... Rf8 30. Nf5 { Of course this jump had been in the pipeline for a while. }
30... Rfe8 { Mate follows after   30...gxf5 ?  31.Rg3+  Kh8  32.Qf6+  . } 31.
Nh6+
{ Better than collecting the exchange, White presses ahead with the attack. }
31... Kf8 32. Qf6 Ng7 33. Rcf3
{ Here the former world champion misses a chance - though his strategic advantage ensures that the win is in no danger anyway.  The beautiful   33.Nf5 !  would have seen White crash through immediately:  gxf5  34.Rg3  Re6  35.Qxg7+  Ke7  36.Qg5+  Kf8  37.Qxf5  f6  38.Qg5  . }
33... Rc8 34. Nxf7 { White finds a way to cash in. } 34... Re6
{ 34...Rxf7  35.Qxf7+  Qxf7  36.Rxf7+  Kg8  37.Rxb7  is no better. } 35. Qg5
Nf5 36. Nh6 Qg7 37. g4
{ Arguably simpler would have been   37.Nxf5  gxf5  38.Qxf5+  Ke7  39.Rg3  Qh8  40.Qf7+  Kd8  41.Qxe6  winning. }
*

