1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 Nf6 6. e3 O-O 7. Qc2 c6 8. Bd3
Re8 9. Nf3 Nbd7 10. O-O-O Nf8
{ 10...b5 ??  was suggested by Karpov after the game in order to develop the queen's bishop to b7. This, however, would be met by the basic tactic  11.Nxb5 ! }
11. h3 Be6 12. Kb1 Rc8
{ In a position with opposite castling it's of great importance to get one's attack off the ground as soon as possible. It helps greatly if there is already some weakness in the enemy's king position, and if it isn't there - well, the first priority is to force its creation. }
13. Ng5 { For   13.g4  see the game Petrosian - Ilivitsky, Moscow 1965. } 13...
b5 { In this case it was best to retreat to d7. } 14. Be5
{ Thus Timman forces Black to weaken himself. } 14... h6 15. Nxe6 Nxe6 16. g4
Nd7
{ Karpov wasn't satisfied with this move, but the alternatives aren't better.   16...Qa5  17.Bf5  b4  18.Ne2  c5  19.Bxe6  fxe6  20.dxc5  Rxc5  21.Qg6  was possible, when according to Timman, White has an excellent position. }
17. h4
{ After either   17.Bg3  Bh4  or   17.Ne2  Bh4  the White pawns on the kingside would be blocked. At the cost of a pawn, if need be, White has to play for open lines and thus for an attack. }
17... b4
{ After   17...Bxh4  there follows  18.f4  Be7  19.Bh7+   19.g5 ?  at once is bad on account of  Nxe5  20.dxe5  when Black can sacrifice a piece for three pawns:  Bxg5  21.fxg5  Qxg5  19...Kf8  20.Bf5  and Black is in huge trouble. }
18. Ne2 Bxh4 19. f4 c5 20. Ba6 Be7
{ Or   20...Rc6  21.Bb7   21.Bb5  Rc8  21...Rb6  22.Bxd5  . } 21. Bxc8 Qxc8
{ White has won the exchange, but at the cost of the immediate attack. The challenges are now more technical - no longer can White think about mate, but he must think about preserving the bishop on e5, if he is to convert the extra exchange. }
22. Ng3 f6 23. Rxh6
{ A crushing rook sacrifice.  Also very strong would have been   23.g5  :  23...fxe5  24.gxh6  e4  and now with  25.hxg7  Nxg7  26.Qg2  White breaks through Black's defensive lines. }
23... Nef8
{ 23...gxh6  24.Qg6+  Kf8  25.Nf5  and mate is forced.  Nxe5  26.dxe5  Bd8  27.Nxh6  Qc7  28.Qg8+  Ke7  29.Qf7#  . }
24. Rh3 c4
{ 24...fxe5  25.dxe5  and White wins the d-pawn, after which the rest would really be a matter of technique. }
25. Nf5 fxe5 26. fxe5
{ White now takes back with the f-pawn to breathe new life into his attack.  Black could resist better after   26.dxe5  Nb6   26...Nc5  27.Rxd5  Nd3  28.Rxd3  cxd3  29.Qxc8  ;   26...Qc6  27.Rdh1  27.Rdh1  Kf7  28.Rh7  Nxh7  29.Nh6+  Kf8  30.Qxh7  gxh6  31.Qxh6+  Kf7  32.Qh7+  Kf8  33.Qg6  . }
26... Qc6 27. Rdh1 Ng6 28. Nd6
{ A:   28.Nxg7 !  Kxg7  29.Rh7+  Kg8  30.Rh8+ !  B:   28.Rh7 !  is winning as well.  Bf8  29.Nd6 }
28... Ndf8 29. Nxe8 Qxe8 30. Rh5
{ The best plan. White once again pauses the attack and aims to trade queens and reach an endgame that should be winning due to the superiority of his rooks over Black's tangle of minor pieces.  A: Here   30.Qf5  c3  31.e4  dxe4  32.Qxe4  Qb5  33.d5  boils down to the same thing as in the game.  B: Interesting is   30.e4 !?  which promises White an interesting game as well. }
30... Qc6 31. Qf5 a5
{ 31...Qe6  32.e4 !  dxe4  33.Qxe4  b3  34.d5  Qa6  35.a3  c3  36.d6  c2+  37.Kc1  and White wins. }
32. e6 Qxe6 33. Qxd5
{ Letting your opponent trade is almost always better than trading yourself ! }
33... a4 34. Rc1 c3 35. bxc3 bxc3 36. Rxc3 Qxd5 37. Rxd5 Ne6 38. Kc2 Kf7 39.
Ra5 Ng5 40. Rc6 Ne4 41. Rxa4
{ 41.Rxg6  would have yielded even more material:  Kxg6  42.Re5 } 41... Nf6 42.
Ra7 Nd5 43. Rxg6 Kxg6 44. e4 Nb4+ 45. Kb3 Bf8 46. Rb7 *

