1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c6 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 h6 7. Bxf6 Bxf6 8. Qd2
O-O 9. O-O-O Nd7 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Bd3 b5
{ Black quickly starts his own play with a thrust on the queenside. } 12. g4
{ Since the weakening pawn move ... h7-h6 has been played, White happily takes advantage of this and starts an attack. }
12... g6
{ Black can't stop the pawn-storm, but he can brace himself for it, a critical part of which will be setting up with a bishop on g7. }
13. h4 Bg7
{ The bishop retreats in the intended manner. Black can now answer g4-g5 with ...h6-h5 and h4-h5 with ...g6-g5, so for the foreseeable future the lines to his own king will remain closed. }
14. Rhg1 { 14.g5  h5  15.e4  doesn't work because of the counterstrike  b4 ! }
14... Re8 15. Kb1 a5
{ It is critical that Black first brings a pawn to a4 before he continues with ...b5-b4. This is because ...b5-b4 would otherwise be met with Nc3-a4, stopping the pawn-storm in its tracks. }
16. Rc1 Nb6 17. h5
{ White wants to do something on the light squares, but the plan lacks bite. }
17... g5 18. Bc2 a4
{ Again not   18...b4 ?!  because of  19.Na4  and Black can't make progress. }
19. Qd3 b4 { Now there's no more reason to wait. } 20. Qh7+ Kf8 21. Ne2 Nd7
{ This is a bit 'respectful'.  Perhaps Black could already have opted for   21...b3 !?  . At least one file will be opened towards White's king. After  22.Bf5  Bxf5+  23.gxf5  Black should then opt for the thematic  a3 !  The shield around White's king will be destroyed and then the Black pieces can flood in.  24.axb3  axb2  25.Rxc6  Nd7  Black is ready for ...Qa5 with a mating attack. }
22. Ng3
{ Too slow. Black takes over now.  Possibly more scary was   22.Nxg5  and White indeed should have played this. Upon the careless  hxg5  Perhaps Black intended   22...Qxg5  23.f4  when one use of the knight move becomes clear:  Nf6 !  24.fxg5  Nxh7  25.Bxh7  hxg5  and Black is clearly better since the queens have been traded.  23.h6  Bf6  24.f4  Ke7  25.Bg6  White has managed to obtain a complete mess in which Black also needs to worry about losing. }
22... Nf6 23. Qd3 Nxg4
{ Black simply removes this pawn from the board and White can do very little about that. }
24. Rg2 Qf6 25. e4
{ Something must be done, but in such a terrible position, it is doomed to fail. }
25... Ba6
{ Well played by Zvjaginsev.  He also had another move at hand:   25...c5 !  prising open the long diagonal. The dark-square bishop cuts through Whites pawns like a knife through butter, for example  26.e5  Nxe5 !  , analogously to the game. }
26. e5 { This is the answer White had in mind. } 26... Nxe5 27. dxe5 Rxe5
{ A strong and principled answer to White's last attempt in the center. } 28.
Nxe5
{ 28.Qd1  is met by  (for example)  Re4 !  and Black delivers mate on the dark squares. }
28... Qxe5
{ Mate on b2 is threatened and White's queen is hanging. The game is over. } *

