[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview Tarrasch"]
[Black "Overview Tarrasch"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
{ If Black wants to strike back in the center at once, the only logical choice is: }
3... c5
{ This is the Tarrasch Defense. Its inventor, Siegbert Tarrasch  (1862-1934)  was not only a strong player, but also a major theoretician of the day. Generally, what happens next is that Black gets to develop his pieces to the most aggressive squares, but all this comes at the cost of accepting an isolated queen's pawn. Initially, it seemed Tarrasch's ideas would not stand the test of time. Since then, views on the IQP have become more balanced. The choice to play with or against such a pawn is largely down to taste. Those who prefer active games  (like Kasparov, who found lots of new ideas in the Tarrasch)  choose to play with such pawns. More experienced players often choose to play against them, but this does not necessarily confer an objective advantage. A major test, for instance, came in the Candidates Match between Kasparov and Smyslov, where the young future champion overcame the ex-champion... }
4. cxd5
{ The most principled move: the silhouette of an IQP is created.   4.Nf3  usually transposes. }
4... exd5
{ An obscure system, though certainly not completely devoid of venom even now, is the Hennig-Schara Gambit:   4...cxd4  Black sacrifices his center pawn for even faster development.  5.Qa4+  Bd7  6.Qxd4  exd5  7.Qxd5  Nc6  8.Nf3  Nf6  9.Qd1  is a usual continuation then. In the Netherlands, there's a player, IM Henk Vedder of the club HSG, who has used this gambit many times. A nice example with various tactical examples is his game against IM Manuel Bosboom. IM Rini Kuijf also used the system several times. He almost managed to scalp GM Jeroen Piket with it. He only 'forgot' in zeitnot to carry out a thematic and decisive combination  (see the game J. Piket - R. Kuijf in a later chapter.)  Play usually continues  Bc5  10.e3  Qe7  11.Be2  O-O-O  or   11...O-O  12.O-O  Rad8  12.O-O  g5 !?  With this thrust, Black initiates an early attack against White's king's position. White would do well to strike back on the other side of the board by means of  13.b4 !?  with an extremely sharp struggle in prospect. We now return to the Tarrasch Defenses main lines. }
5. Nf3 Nc6 6. g3
{ The best way of playing against the isolani in this position. White moves his bishop to the long diagonal where it will exert pressure on d5.  Of course, people also play   6.e3  , but this promises fewer chances of gaining an edge. }
6... Nf6
{ If Black doesn't feel like playing with an isolated pawn, there is also   6...c4  which is the so-called Swedish Variation. Black resolves the tension in the center and in the long turn intends to do business with his pawn majority on the queenside. Yet this is of course not the full story, as White can make inroads on Black's structure through b2-b3 or also Bg2 followed by a well-timed e2-e4. Sometimes White can also add Nf3-e5.  7.Bg2  We're now at crossroads:  Bb4  This bishop move is very popular. It prevents White from pushing b2-b3 to attack Black's pawn structure, at least for now, and introduces the idea of permanently preventing this option through the exchange ...Bb4xc3  (which will also make e3-e4 harder to execute.)  Less played is   7...Nf6  . Black's problem is that the knight on f6 can be pinned by Bg5, the result being that he'll be stuck with doubled pawns on f6 and f7. A possible sequence then would be  8.O-O  Be7  9.Bg5  O-O  10.Ne5  This is a characteristic move White will be working with. Of course, Black can't trade on e5, because he'd lose a pawn, and White intends to give his opponent doubled pawns on c6 and c4 by playing Nxc6. At first sight, this seems to work to Black's advantage, since a pawn on c6 would support his center pawn on d5. This is true, but White has b2-b3 in mind, exploiting the doubled pawns by exchanging one of them ! The remaining one will find itself exposed on a half-open file. For instance:  10...Be6  11.Nxc6  bxc6  12.b3  cxb3  13.axb3  and the resulting structure is very favorable to White. Such developments occurred in, inter alia, Nielsen - Rogers, 2006.  8.O-O  Nge7  and now:  9.e4  White should no longer wait. He'll have the best chance of gaining an edge if he immediately puts pressure on the center.  With   9.Ne5  White can open the diagonal for his bishop on g2 and thus he'll try to maim Blacks pawn structure. At the same time, he's preparing the thematic push e2-e4. However, this is all somewhat too slow because Black has no problems after  O-O  10.e4  Be6  A nice example is the game Beliavsky - Xu, 1992, where Black replied  9...O-O  with complications. }
7. Bg2 Be7 8. O-O O-O
{ This is the basic position in the Tarrasch Defense, in which many ways of playing have been suggested and tried by White players. For now, I will confine myself to an outline of those methods which have associated games in the section on practical examples. }
9. Bg5
{ This is considered to be White's most principled continuation. The pressure on Black's center has now reached the point where he must commit.  White has another important option though: a very interesting approach is to play   9.dxc5  at once. After  Bxc5  10.Bg5   10.Na4  was once played by Giri in his game against Jianu, 2012.  10...d4  11.Bxf6  Qxf6  the consensus for a while was that White had only gained a minimal edge. Until, that is, the Dutch GM Jan Timman introduced a new concept, namely  12.Nd5 !?  A very drawish variation is   12.Ne4  Qe7  13.Nxc5  Qxc5  . Black has enough counterplay to compensate for the weakness on d4.  12...Qd8  13.Nd2  We've reached a position where the extent of White's advantage was unveiled in the seventies and eighties by strategists like Karpov, Timman, and Andersson. Timman considered this finding as one of his most important contributions to opening theory. His game against Ivkov of 1977  (see the appendix with games)  illustrates beautifully what plans White can aim for. White has many strategic ideas in this position. He can maneuver his knight from d5 to the nice square d3, where it will block the isolated pawn on d4 very well  (though this should be delayed until Black expends tempi on chasing it away from its annoying post)  . Furthermore White can pressure Blacks position by maneuvering on the queenside, for instance: Rc1, Nd2-c4 or Nd2-b3. We can see that in exchange for the bishop-pair White has obtained extremely good prospects for quite a few pieces. The general idea is to use the light squares to put Black's position under pressure. The bishop on g2 is extremely powerful, so Black should try to trade it. But even if he manages this, he'll be left with a bad bishop due to the pawn on d4. This pawn tends to be a weakness, in spite of the occasional tactical tricks it can generate. White can use the c-file for carrying out a few different plans. It was the strategic focus of some great games, such as Andersson - Nunn, 1980 in the chapter on model games. A brief note on Black's counterplay: it can, in spite of all Ive said, become significant; one example was Hauser - Perunovi, 2012. Before getting back to the main move 9. Bg5, let us also mention that White has tried   9.Be3  ,   9.Bf4  and   9.b3  . }
9... cxd4
{ Black usually feels forced to trade, at which point the long-inevitable IQP finally takes definitive form. }
10. Nxd4 h6
{ Black tries to reduce the pressure by forcing the important White bishop to make a choice. }
11. Be3
{ Here the bishop will stand best. We'll soon see why this is the case.   11.Bf4  is also played sometimes. }
11... Re8
{ A useful waiting move. As usual for double-edged positions, I will give one reference for White and one for Black. triumphed in the game Kasparov - Illescas, 1994, where there soon appeared 'hanging pawns'  (on c6 and d5)  , which he managed to block. Then he won a pawn and flawlessly brought the remaining endgame to an end. The other side of the coin was seen in Zhao Xue - Petrosian, where in exchange for his weak pawn structure, Black got an attack against White's king, finishing with an unusual combination. }
12. Rc1 Bf8 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Na4
{ Black now has 'hanging pawns' on c6 and d5. Together they can be strong if they can stand side by side on the 5th rank. But with the last move Nc3-a4, White prevents this and seems likely to soon occupy square c5 with a piece. Before doing so he might also trade the dark-square bishops. Black would then be stuck with a bad light-square bishop and if the pawns can be blocked by White's pieces, they'll remain weak until the far endgame. Nonetheless, it's not easy that to execute this strategic plan. Black has counterplay against the e2-pawn  (for example after .. .Bc8-g4)  and he can also focus some attention on White's king's position. The advance of the h-pawn can lead to weaknesses and together with a possible knight move to e4 Black will obtain the necessary counterplay. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview Tarrasch"]
[Black "Tarrasch: 4.cxd5 cxd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
{ If Black wants to strike back in the center at once, the only logical choice is: }
3... c5
{ This is the Tarrasch Defense. Its inventor, Siegbert Tarrasch  (1862-1934)  was not only a strong player, but also a major theoretician of the day. Generally, what happens next is that Black gets to develop his pieces to the most aggressive squares, but all this comes at the cost of accepting an isolated queen's pawn. Initially, it seemed Tarrasch's ideas would not stand the test of time. Since then, views on the IQP have become more balanced. The choice to play with or against such a pawn is largely down to taste. Those who prefer active games  (like Kasparov, who found lots of new ideas in the Tarrasch)  choose to play with such pawns. More experienced players often choose to play against them, but this does not necessarily confer an objective advantage. A major test, for instance, came in the Candidates Match between Kasparov and Smyslov, where the young future champion overcame the ex-champion... }
4. cxd5
{ The most principled move: the silhouette of an IQP is created.  An obscure system, though certainly not completely devoid of venom even now, is the Hennig-Schara Gambit: }
4... cxd4 { Black sacrifices his center pawn for even faster development. } 5.
Qa4+ Bd7 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Qxd5 Nc6 8. Nf3 Nf6 9. Qd1
{ is a usual continuation then. In the Netherlands, there's a player, IM Henk Vedder of the club HSG, who has used this gambit many times. A nice example with various tactical examples is his game against IM Manuel Bosboom. IM Rini Kuijf also used the system several times. He almost managed to scalp GM Jeroen Piket with it. He only 'forgot' in zeitnot to carry out a thematic and decisive combination  (see the game J. Piket - R. Kuijf in a later chapter)  Play usually continues }
9... Bc5 10. e3 Qe7 11. Be2 O-O-O 12. O-O g5
{ With this thrust, Black initiates an early attack against White's king's position. White would do well to strike back on the other side of the board by means of }
13. b4
{ with an extremely sharp struggle in prospect. We now return to the Tarrasch Defenses main lines. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview Tarrasch"]
[Black "Tarrasch: 4.cxd5 exd5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
{ If Black wants to strike back in the center at once, the only logical choice is: }
3... c5
{ This is the Tarrasch Defense. Its inventor, Siegbert Tarrasch  (1862-1934)  was not only a strong player, but also a major theoretician of the day. Generally, what happens next is that Black gets to develop his pieces to the most aggressive squares, but all this comes at the cost of accepting an isolated queen's pawn. Initially, it seemed Tarrasch's ideas would not stand the test of time. Since then, views on the IQP have become more balanced. The choice to play with or against such a pawn is largely down to taste. Those who prefer active games  (like Kasparov, who found lots of new ideas in the Tarrasch)  choose to play with such pawns. More experienced players often choose to play against them, but this does not necessarily confer an objective advantage. A major test, for instance, came in the Candidates Match between Kasparov and Smyslov, where the young future champion overcame the ex-champion... }
4. cxd5 { The most principled move: the silhouette of an IQP is created. } 4...
exd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. g3
{ The best way of playing against the isolani in this position. White moves his bishop to the long diagonal where it will exert pressure on d5.   If Black doesn't feel like playing with an isolated pawn, there is also }
6... c4
{ which is the so-called Swedish Variation. Black resolves the tension in the center and in the long turn intends to do business with his pawn majority on the queenside. Yet this is of course not the full story, as White can make inroads on Black's structure through b2-b3 or also Bg2 followed by a well-timed e2-e4. Sometimes White can also add Nf3-e5. }
7. Bg2 { Were now at crossroads:  Less played is } 7... Nf6
{ . Blacks problem is that the knight on f6 can be pinned by Bg5, the result being that he'll be stuck with doubled pawns on f6 and f7. A possible sequence then would be }
8. O-O Be7 9. Bg5 O-O 10. Ne5
{ This is a characteristic move White will be working with. Of course, Black can't trade on e5 because he'd lose a pawn, and White intends to give his opponent doubled pawns on c6 and c4 by playing Nxc6. At first sight, this seems to work to Black's advantage, since a pawn on c6 would support his center pawn on d5. This is true, but White has b2-b3 in mind, exploiting the doubled pawns by exchanging one of them ! The remaining one will find itself exposed on a half-open file. For instance: }
10... Be6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. b3 cxb3 13. axb3
{ and the resulting structure is very favorable to White. Such developments occurred in, inter alia, Nielsen - Rogers, 2006. }
