[White "Overview Tarrasch"]
[Black "Tarrasch: 6...Nf6 and 9.Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
{ If Black wants to strike back in the center at once, the only logical choice is: }
3... c5
{ This is the Tarrasch Defense. Its inventor, Siegbert Tarrasch  (1862-1934)  was not only a strong player, but also a major theoretician of the day. Generally, what happens next is that Black gets to develop his pieces to the most aggressive squares, but all this comes at the cost of accepting an isolated queen's pawn. Initially, it seemed Tarrasch's ideas would not stand the test of time. Since then, views on the IQP have become more balanced. The choice to play with or against such a pawn is largely down to taste. Those who prefer active games  (like Kasparov, who found lots of new ideas in the Tarrasch)  choose to play with such pawns. More experienced players often choose to play against them, but this does not necessarily confer an objective advantage. A major test, for instance, came in the Candidate's Match between Kasparov and Smyslov, where the young future champion overcame the ex-champion... }
4. cxd5 { The most principled move: the silhouette of an IQP is created. } 4...
exd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. g3
{ The best way of playing against the isolani in this position. White moves his bishop to the long diagonal where it will exert pressure on d5. }
6... Nf6 7. Bg2 Be7 8. O-O O-O
{ This is the basic position in the Tarrasch Defense, in which many ways of playing have been suggested and tried by White players. For now, I will confine myself to an outline of those methods which have associated games in the section on practical examples. }
9. Bg5
{ This is considered to be White's most principled continuation. The pressure on Black's center has now reached the point where he must commit. }
9... cxd4
{ Black usually feels forced to trade, at which point the long-inevitable IQP finally takes definitive form. }
10. Nxd4 h6
{ Black tries to reduce the pressure by forcing the important White bishop to make a choice. }
11. Be3
{ Here the bishop will stand best. We'll soon see why this is the case. } 11...
Re8
{ A useful waiting move. As usual for double-edged positions, I will give one reference for White and one for Black. White triumphed in the game Kasparov - Illescas, 1994, where there soon appeared 'hanging pawns'  (on c6 and d5)  , which he managed to block. Then he won a pawn and flawlessly brought the remaining endgame to an end. The other side of the coin was seen in Zhao Xue - Petrosian, where in exchange for his weak pawn structure, Black got an attack against White's king, finishing with an unusual combination. }
12. Rc1 Bf8 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Na4
{ Black now has 'hanging pawns' on c6 and d5. Together they can be strong if they can stand side by side on the 5th rank. But with the last move Nc3-a4, White prevents this and seems likely to soon occupy square c5 with a piece. Before doing so he might also trade the dark-square bishops. Black would then be stuck with a bad light-square bishop and if the pawns can be blocked by White's pieces, theyll remain weak until the far endgame. Nonetheless, it's not easy that to execute this strategic plan. Black has counterplay against the e2-pawn  (for example after .. .Bc8-g4)  and he can also focus some attention on White's king's position. The advance of the h-pawn can lead to weaknesses and together with a possible knight move to e4 Black will obtain the necessary counterplay. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview Noteboom"]
[Black "Overview Noteboom"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c6
{ With his last move Black has indicated he may want to play the Noteboom Variation, named after the Dutch chess player Daniel Noteboom  (1910-1932)  . He was very talented and although he went to study mathematics at Leiden University, his academic career was ultimately curtailed by playing too much chess  (!)  . He played for the Netherlands in Hamburg in 1930, and in Prague in 1931. He died unexpectedly at the age of 21 from pneumonia and bronchitis. }
4. Nf3
{ White shows he doesn't care about the c4-pawn.  White can also play the famous gambit line:   4.e4  dxe4  5.Nxe4  Bb4+  6.Bd2  Qxd4  7.Bxb4  Qxe4+  when most people believe that a well-prepared Black player should not lose, though of course there are numerous lines to remember, for instance:  8.Ne2   8.Be2  is also played here.  8...Qxc4  9.Bf8 !?  with enormous complications.  or   9.Qd6  Nd7  Many White players would opt for   4.e3  because they don't like the idea of Black taking on c4, after which there could arise transpositions to the Slav Defense. }
4... dxc4
{ There is, of course, also   4...Nf6  Black transposing to the Semi-Slav. } 5.
e3
{ By means of   5.a4  White can prevent the upcoming advance ...b7-b5 for a while, but not in the long term, as after  Bb4  the knight on c3 will be pinned and ...b7-b5 is again in the pipeline. We will transpose back to the main line, as discussed below.  But first, we should check another critical-looking option:   5.e4 !?  By comparison to the main line, though, it transpires that following an almost-forced sequence, this ambitiously thrusted pawn will turn out to be hanging.  b5  6.a4  Bb4  7.Bd2  a5  8.axb5  Bxc3  9.Bxc3  cxb5  10.b3  Bb7  . White has no good way of protecting e4, so he must instead try and blast all the central lines open. With his next move White threatens Bxg7.  11.d5  Nf6  12.bxc4  b4  Now we see that White's activity has been premature. }
5... b5
{ As promised, Black hangs onto the pawn and he'll only give it back if something else is offered in exchange. }
6. a4 Bb4 { More of the same. } 7. Bd2
{ White neutralizes the pin, threatening to win back the pawn again. } 7... a5
{ Initiating a queenside armada.   7...Bb7  now usually transposes. } 8. axb5
Bxc3
{ It's a huge concession to give up this beautiful bishop, but it does fit the plan. Soon we'll see where we're headed. }
9. Bxc3 cxb5 10. b3 Bb7
{ The rook on a8 needs covering since the next move only works if the a5-pawn isn't pinned.  Clearly,   10...cxb3 ?!  11.Bxb5+  Bd7  12.Qxb3  isn't desirable. }
11. bxc4 b4 12. Bb2
{ White seems to have got all that he could possibly wish for: a strong pawn center, the bishop pair and a nice passed pawn on the c-file. Black, on the other hand, has a formidable weapon: connected past pawns on the a- and b-files. In many games, these proved to be the decisive factor. A nice example that illustrates this is Sadler - Krasenkow. On the other hand, sometimes those Black pawns can be tamed and White's center be unfurled in its full glory, as in the games Kasparov - Tyomkin and Van Wely - Alekseev. }
*

