1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c6
{ With his last move Black has indicated he may want to play the Noteboom Variation, named after the Dutch chess player Daniel Noteboom  (1910-1932)  . He was very talented and although he went to study mathematics at Leiden University, his academic career was ultimately curtailed by playing too much chess  (!)  . He played for the Netherlands in Hamburg in 1930, and in Prague in 1931. He died unexpectedly at the age of 21 from pneumonia and bronchitis. }
4. Nf3 { White shows he doesn't care about the c4-pawn. } 4... dxc4
{ From the moment Black captures the pawn on c4, the Noteboom variation is close to inevitable. The pawn won't be given back without a struggle, and White has to give Black connected passers in order to get it back, making the game very sharp. }
5. e3 b5
{ As promised, Black hangs onto the pawn and he'll only give it back if something else is offered in exchange. }
