{ White neutralizes the pin, threatening to win back the pawn again. } 7... a5
{ Initiating a queenside armada. } 8. axb5 Bxc3
{ It's a huge concession to give up this beautiful bishop, but it does fit the plan. Soon we'll see where we're headed. }
9. Bxc3 cxb5 10. b3 Bb7
{ The rook on a8 needs covering since the next move only works if the a5-pawn isn't pinned. }
11. bxc4 b4 12. Bb2
{ White seems to have got all that he could possibly wish for: a strong pawn center, the bishop pair and a nice passed pawn on the c-file. Black, on the other hand, has a formidable weapon: connected past pawns on the a- and b-files. In many games, these proved to be the decisive factor. A nice example that illustrates this is Sadler - Krasenkow. On the other hand, sometimes those Black pawns can be tamed and White's center be unfurled in its full glory, as in the games Kasparov - Tyomkin and Van Wely - Alekseev. }
