[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview Ragozin"]
[Black "Overview Ragozin"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 { Now a major choice is: } 4... Bb4
{ which is called the Ragozin Variation. Black aims for a quick ...c5 and after ...h7-h6, Bg5-h4 g7-g5, Bh4-g3 he'll start playing with tactical ideas like ...Nf6-e4 and...Qd8-a5 in order to increase the pressure on Nc3 quickly. }
5. cxd5
{ This trade on d5 is played frequently. The most important reason is to pre-empt Black's c5 by making him aware that it will result in having an IQP.  There is a strategic option available for those players who don't like the tactical mess of the main line:   5.Qa4+  Black's next move is forced and then customary is the continuation:  Nc6  6.e3  O-O  7.Nf3  h6  Black still wants White's bishop to make up its mind.  8.Bxf6  Analogously to many variations in the Queen's Gambit, White gives up the bishop pair when not strictly forced to, in exchange for a fixed pawn structure, in which he hopes his knights will function better than Black's bishops.  Of course,   8.Bh4  is also possible. Black usually proceeds with  Bd7  , after which ... Nxd4 ! is suddenly threatening because the bishop is taboo due to the knight fork on c2. In Le - Mahjoob, 2008 White played  9.Qc2  and was later victorious after a sharp and unstable game.  8...Qxf6  9.cxd5  exd5  10.Be2  Be6  11.O-O  a6  12.Rfc1  This is a typical structure that has occurred rather often in grandmaster practice. White aims for the minority attack with a2-a3 and b2-b4. By trading the right pieces he can control the evolution of the position quite tightly. Magnus Carlsen gave us a demonstration in his game against Aronian from Wijk aan Zee 2015. }
5... exd5 6. Nf3 h6
{ This is the sharpest continuation. Let us illustrate another playable Black idea:   6...Nbd7  7.e3  Now comes the sharp  c5  8.Qc2  Most often, the specific order used to reach such positions isn't 8. Qc2 but:   8.Bd3  Qa5  9.O-O  Now after  c4  10.Bf5  O-O  we reach a key position for this line.  Meanwhile, taking on c3 is inadvisable:   10...Bxc3  11.bxc3  Qxc3  12.Bxf6  Nxf6  13.Qa4+  Bd7  14.Bxd7+  Nxd7  15.Qb5  and White won back his pawn with interest, as was demonstrated in Sulashvili - Gonzalez Garcia, 2007.  Now play generally continues:  11.Qc2  Re8  12.Nd2  g6  13.Bxd7  Nxd7  In this position, there have been many ideas tested in practice.  14.f3  preparing the center advance e3-e4 is played most often. However, in Korobov - Wang, 2011 this didn't end well for White.  Meanwhile, the above-mentioned 2014 encounter Kramnik - Mamedyarov reached this point by transposition and continued   14.h4  .  8...Qa5  9.Bd3  c4 !  The idea is to form a queenside pawn majority, which Black will try to exploit in the endgame. Initially, in Svidler - Kramnik, 2010 White didn't manage to get his initiative off the ground  (either in the center or on the kingside.)  Then Black created a passed pawn on the queenside that secured victory. Later it was especially Kramnik himself who showed the correct treatment of White's position, still starting with the same move  10.Bf5  ; firstly, in the rapid game Kramnik - Grischuk, 2010 he pushed a quick e3-e4 through and exchanged off the c4-pawn. Deep in the endgame, his bishop demonstrated superiority over a sidelined Black knight. Secondly, he then played a beautiful positional game against Mamedyarov in 2014. After a trade on c3, White placed his bishop on f4 and claimed the b-file for his rooks. Later he made clever use of this. }
7. Bh4
{ Of course, White can also here trade his bishop for the knight with   7.Bxf6  Qxf6  after which White can transpose to the above-mentioned lines with Qa4+.  Meanwhile, of independent interest is  8.Qb3  . After that, Black will generally proceed with his usual plan and play  c5  . In this variation too, which I omit further discussion of for space reasons, we can see all kinds of top-class names taking one or other side }
7... g5
{ In for a penny, in for a pound !  The older way of playing was   7...c5  8.e3  and now  g5  9.Bg3  Ne4  10.Bb5+  Kf8 ?!  A remarkable move. Black renounces his right to castle because he's betting on the poor placement of White's bishop on b5. An early Ragozin specialist, grandmaster Genna Sosonko, once prepared this surprise continuation for a big game  One would expect   10...Bd7  here, but Black would rather not trade the light-squared bishops. Black wants, if possible, to set his majority into motion by means of ...Bb4xc3 and sometimes ...c5-c4. In those positions, in addition to the obvious tactics of ...Nxc3 forking the queen and light-square bishop, White's b5-bishop can often be embarrassed in other, more subtle ways.  However, unfortunately for him, his opponent was the young Garry Kasparov, who was ready with the following answer when the two played in the Interpolistoernooi in Tilburg in 1981:  11.dxc5 !!  Behind this lies a brilliant concept.  Nxc3  12.bxc3  Bxc3+  13.Ke2  Bxa1  14.Qxa1  f6  It's time to take stock of the position. White has sacrificed the exchange, but has obtained an abundance of compensation in various forms:   - Development and activity   - Bishop pair in an open position   - Unsafe Black king   - Better pawn structure   - Control over d6, which can be used as a outpost by several of Whites pieces   - A position in which diagonals are more important than files.   The second and last of these aspects were perhaps the most evident in the further evolution of the game. We can see the game  (and the manner in which Kasparov used the raking bishops)  in the section with Model Games. }
8. Bg3 Ne4
{ At the cost of substantial weaknesses, Black has created two tricky threats: the obvious one is ...Nxc3 but there's also ...h5, putting the g3-bishop in danger. It transpired after numerous practical tests that White's best chance is to opt for a positional pawn sacrifice: }
9. Nd2
{ At the  (temporary)  cost of a pawn the strong black knight on e4 is forced away. }
9... Nxc3 10. bxc3 Bxc3 11. Rc1 Bb2
{ If Black wants to keep his extra pawn, he'll have to compete with White's very strong bishop pair for the rest of the game.  This could happen after   11...Bxd2+  12.Qxd2  when in the game Gajewski - Wernert, 2012 White succeeded in converting his advantage into victory. }
12. Bxc7 Qe7 13. Bd6 { A very interesting attacking game is in prospect. } *

