[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 { Now a major choice is: } 4... Bb4
{ There is a strategic option available for those players who don't like the tactical mess of the main line: }
5. Qa4+ { Black's next move is forced and then customary is the continuation: }
5... Nc6 6. e3 O-O 7. Nf3 h6
{ Black still wants White's bishop to make up its mind. } 8. Bxf6
{ Analogously to many variations in the Queen's Gambit, White gives up the bishop pair when not strictly forced to, in exchange for a fixed pawn structure, in which he hopes his knights will function better than Black's bishops. }
8... Qxf6 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Be2 Be6 11. O-O a6 12. Rfc1
{ This is a typical structure that has occurred rather often in grandmaster practice. White aims for the minority attack with a2-a3 and b2-b4. By trading the right pieces he can control the evolution of the position quite tightly. Magnus Carlsen gave us a demonstration in his game against Aronian from Wijk aan Zee 2015. }
