1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 { Now a major choice is: } 4... Bb4
{ which is called the Ragozin Variation. Black aims for a quick ...c5 and after ...h7-h6, Bg5-h4 g7-g5, Bh4-g3 he'll start playing with tactical ideas like ...Nf6-e4 and...Qd8-a5 in order to increase the pressure on Nc3 quickly. }
5. cxd5
{ This trade on d5 is played frequently. The most important reason is to pre-empt Black's c5 by making him aware that it will result in having an IQP. }
5... exd5 6. Nf3 Nbd7 7. e3 { Now comes the sharp } 7... c5
{ Most often, the specific order used to reach such positions isn't 8. Qc2 but: }
8. Bd3 Qa5 9. O-O { Now after } 9... c4 10. Bf5
{ Meanwhile, taking on c3 is inadvisable: } 10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 Qxc3 12. Bxf6
Nxf6 13. Qa4+ Bd7 14. Bxd7+ Nxd7 15. Qb5
{ and White won back his pawn with interest, as was demonstrated in Sulashvili - Gonzalez Garcia, 2007. }
