[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview Cambridge Springs"]
[Black "Overview Cambridge Springs"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Nbd7 5. e3
{ Now   5.cxd5  exd5  is a common trap. This seems to win a pawn, but in fact, it loses a piece.  6.Nxd5 ?  Black's answer is surprising:  Nxd5 !  Seemingly blundering the queen, but Black is winning when after  7.Bxd8  he wins his material back with interest.  Bb4+  8.Qd2  Bxd2+  9.Kxd2  Kxd8 }
5... c6
{ Bringing about the old and famous Cambridge Springs structure. The move is vaguely Slav-like and gives Black a choice besides the Carlsbad option in case White were to trade on d5. }
6. Nf3
{ After   6.cxd5  Black is likely to take back the c-pawn:  cxd5  after which a symmetrical pawn structure has arisen with a symbolic edge for White. What White has here tends not to be enough to play for a win, though it must be said that Blacks d7-knight would much prefer to be on c6. }
6... Qa5
{ This is the main idea in the Cambridge Springs. Black's pieces are swarming forwards in hell-for-leather fashion. He'll put pressure on Nc3 and White should watch out carefully in order to not stand worse soon. }
7. Qc2 Bb4
{ As expected. Also relevant to our exposition is the immediate:   7...Ne4  Now White has two important replies:  8.cxd5  if he wants to preserve the bishop pair, he'll move away his queen's bishop but after   8.Bf4  Bb4  9.Rc1  Qxa2  , Black has simply taken a pawn. It's questionable whether White's compensation is enough. In Mitsakos - Castellano Ojeda, 1993 it wasn't. Worse still: White lost in 19 moves...  8...exd5  9.Bd3  White keeps on developing.   9.Bf4  Bb4  10.Rc1  has the same problem as before: Black can again play  Qxa2  and be a full pawn up.  9...Nxg5  10.Nxg5  h6  11.Nf3  Bd6  12.O-O  ; here White has brought all his minor pieces into the game while Black has yet to do the same. The knight has to move again in order to activate the queen's bishop. White's superb score in this position is therefore unsurprising, and a good exposition was provided in Savchenko - Mahmud, 1997, where Black was overrun on the kingside. }
8. Nd2 O-O
{ Also possible is   8...dxc4  at once, after which  9.Bxf6  Nxf6  10.Nxc4  Qc7  11.a3  Be7  leads to a position which can very soon be classed as leading to two results as soon as White finds a way to prevent Black from freeing himself through ...c6-c5. In a number of games, among them Kasparov - Averbakh, 1982 and in Ribli - Smyslov, 1982, White was successful in doing this and eventually won. In Tunik - Bondarenko, 1999, Black instead tried to free himself by more drastic means, but these were refuted. }
9. Be2
{ Here we have a couple of variations:  A well-known piece blunder is:   9.Bd3 ??  dxc4 !  Suddenly both bishops are hanging !  If White wants to post the bishop on d3, he should trade on f6 first:   9.Bxf6  Nxf6  10.Bd3  With his last move, White stays flexible, prioritising quick development. He's also waiting to see how Black tries to free his game. White, though, still has to castle so Black has a little time to do this and solve the Bc8 problem. There are various pushes Black can play for to this end. The most important ones are e5  (perhaps preceded by ...d5xc4)  , dxc4, and ... c5. Notably, e5 is preferred by many top-class players and is considered the standard way to liberate Blacks game. It's also quite normal to play for ...c6-c5. Black even won with this push in the nice game Babujian-Shanava, 2004. Fun fact: after Whites 10th move the database shows an old rapid game Carlsen - Kasparov, Reykjavik 2004. The current world champion was still very young, but calculated the complications well, failing only in the conversion of his extra pawn right at the end... }
9... e5 { With a position that has been played scores of times. } *

