[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview Carlsbad"]
[Black "Overview Carlsbad: Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
{ With the immediate   3.cxd5  exd5  White can opt for the Exchange Variation, bringing about the famous Carlsbad structure, as it is known in the literature. White can do this at various times, of which the most accurate may be move 4 - so we'll consider it there. }
3... Nf6
{ Black's developing his king's knight, protecting his center pawn and bringing us to the main line. However, before we go further, it's important to talk about other move orders Black can use. The first and most important is to avoid the pin Bg5 by means of playing ...Be7 first.   3...Be7  By playing this way Black intends to delay the development of his king's knight and make other useful moves first. This makes the Exchange Variation less appealing. One important plan is to play a quick ...Bf5 after cxd5 exd5.  4.cxd5  Since Black hasn't played ...Nf6, White could consider   4.e4  at once. But this won't promise him anything.  dxe4  5.Nxe4  Nf6  6.Nxf6+  Bxf6  7.Nf3  c5  Black has solved his opening problems.  4...exd5  5.Bf4  This bishop should come out first before White moves the king's pawn forward with e2-e3.  c6  Black is now ready to prepare the liberating ...Bc8-f5.   5...Bf5 ?  would be a mistake after  6.Qb3 !  The reason is that two pawns are hanging  (d5 and b7)  and so he will lose something without any obvious compensation.  6.e3  Now Black is ready for the development of his bishop, since Qb3 is met by ...Qb6.  It seems logical for White to continue with   6.Qc2  so that Black still can't play ...Bf5. However, Black will proceed with  g6  , after which ...Bf5 can't be prevented anymore. One could wonder whether ...g6 might create a significant weakness, but in practice, there isn't anything to worry about - and getting a bishop on f5 is more important than this small weakness on the kingside. Whatever weakness there might be is near-impossible to exploit.  6...Bf5  Black's plan seems to have worked and if he could also develop his king's knight, it would be impossible to disrupt the rest of his development. However, right now, it is White's move, and he can use the narrow window of time:  7.g4 !?  This places Black's queen's bishop in a tough spot: retreat to e6, after which White can move his king's bishop to the beautiful square d3; or to g6, in the path of the oncoming pawn-storm ?  Be6  Probably the most logical square to retreat to; the position became a basis for debate in a World Championship match: Botvinnik took White twice, and Petrosian Black. The result was two famous games between the combatants - fittingly, one win for White and one for Black  (see chapter 5)  .  For now let us briefly investigate   7...Bg6  Black has prevented White from placing his bishop on the ideal square d3, but theres a snag:  8.h4 !?  So, that only leaves  h5  , since we've just seen it isn't sensible for Black to take the pawn on h4.  A promising pawn sacrifice. The pawn can't really be taken with   8...Bxh4  due to  9.Qb3  and Black is in big trouble. The queen has to keep protecting the bishop on h4, but the b7-pawn is hanging.  b6  is the only real answer, but this is just a horrible weakening of the pawn structure. White can already carry out a deadly combination:  10.Rxh4 !  Qxh4  11.Nxd5  and White is completely winning.  In the old game Karpov - Portisch, 1989 White played  9.g5  and won later. So Petrosian was right ! Let us now return to the main lines. As mentioned before, move 4 is the best time for White to exchange on d5, if he's going to. }
4. cxd5 { Entering the Exchange Variation. } 4... exd5
{ From now on the pawn structure will be fixed for a rather long time and both sides' plans can be well mapped out. The Carlsbad structure were in now has had ardent and partisan supporters on both sides for decades. }
5. Bg5
{ The most accurate move. It's important for White to keep preventing the liberating bishop move ...Bc8-f5 or at least to make it as unappealing as possible. }
5... Be7
{ Again Black plays the obvious continuation, neutralizing the pin and preparing to castle. For that reason 5. Nf3 c6 6. Bg5  wouldn't be so accurate on account of  Bf5  and Black has solved most of his problems.  A reasonable attempt at move-order subtlety, though, is:   5...c6  with the idea of threatening ...Bf5. White now has two different ways of playing which we'll discuss seperately. Option 1:  6.Qc2  Option 2:   6.e3 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview Carlsbad"]
[Black "Overview Carlsbad: 5...c6 6.Qc2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. Qc2
{ This is an interesting move, preventing the positional threat of Bf5. Black now has two options. The normal continuation is }
6... Be7
{ Maybe   6...g6  is justified here: after all, Black wants to play ...Bf5. This also seems tactically justified:  7.Nxd5  Also after   7.Bxf6  Qxf6  8.Nxd5  Qxd4  9.Rd1  Bb4+  10.Nxb4  Qxb4+  the chances are about equal.  7...Qxd5  8.Bxf6  Bb4+  9.Kd1  O-O  and practice has demonstrated Black has enough compensation for the pawn. For example:  10.e4  Re8  11.Bd3  Bf5  12.f3  Nd7 !?  13.Ne2  Nxf6  14.exd5  Nxd5  15.Qb1  c5  Vladimirov - Diaz, 1986. }
7. e3 { when White succeeds in preventing the bishop trade. } 7... Nbd7 8. Bd3
{ and now another split: } 8... O-O
{ After this move, White is faced with a significant choice of plan- the same choice from chapter 2, now made concrete. Here there are three important approaches:   - The plan of Ng1-f3 followed by castling short and then Ra1-b1 and b2-b4 is called the minority attack. The plan has already been covered in some detail, together with Black response, in chapter 2. Here we'll repeat some aspects and supplement them with variations and references to some important games.   - The plan of Ng1-e2, castling short and then Ra1-e1 follow by a well-timed f2-f3. In this way White aims to push e3-e4  (-e5)  .   - There is also a plan of O-O-O, either with the g1-knight on f3 or e2. The intention is to set up an attack against Black's king with g2-g4 and h2-h4, usually followed by g4-g5 and/or h4-h5.  An important alternative now is:   8...Nh5  9.Bxe7  Qxe7  10.Nge2  with the intention of continuing with  g6  in order to prepare ...Ng7, .. .Nb6 and ...Nf5. Not only does Black want to trade his bad bishop, but he may also, for the first time, be thinking seriously about long castling.  We now give attention to these three plans: }
9. Nf3
{ White can play   9.Nge2  . This has various advantages. One is that the knight can be brought into the game via g3; another advantage is White can play to create a strong pawn center with f2-f3 and e3-e4. A possible continuation now is  Re8  10.O-O  Nf8  11.f3  Be6  12.Rae1  World champion Mikhail Botvinnik had this system in his repertoire, and his pupil - and later world champion - Garry Kasparov also became a great supporter of this plan, as can be seen from, inter alia, the game Kasparov - Andersson, 1988.   9.O-O-O  With the king on the queenside, the battle suddenly becomes sharp.  Re8  After this, the alternative development of the White king's knight - to e2 - once again becomes a very serious option. Obviously,  10.Nf3  is always an option.  In this way White gets a big advantage, which we can illustrate best by means of a concrete example:   10.Nge2  Nf8  11.h3  a5  12.Kb1  b5  13.g4  a4  and now the knight can go the nice square g3. In the game Vladimirov - Van der Sterren, 1990, White soon got a dangerous attack, while Black didnt get any play on the queenside  (see the chapter Model Games for details.)  The game now usually goes as follows:  10...Nf8  11.h3  Be6  12.Kb1  Rc8  Now the struggle becomes really interesting. As mentioned elsewhere, in order to develop a truly meaningful attack for either side, it will become necessary to force weaknesses in the opponent's king position. Black has another plan as well. He can try blasting open the center by means of ...c6-c5. Although this means accepting an isolated pawn on d5, there will be some compensating piece activity. As a rule, Blacks chances in this position aren't worse. We now return to the origin of all this complexity. }
9... Re8 10. O-O Nf8 11. Rab1
{ and again we now have the basic position for a minority attack on the board. Both players have a half-open file, White the c-file and Black the e-file. However, directing a rook towards one of these lines won't do much, since its activity is limited by the boulder on respectively c6 and e3, as has already been discussed earlier. For White it would be more obvious to undermine pawn c6 by launching the action b2-b4-b5. A model game that shows how White puts his plans into effect is Karpov - Ljubojevic, 1989. }
*

