[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview Carlsbad"]
[Black "Overview Carlsbad: 5...c6 6.e3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3
{ White allows Black's bishop to reach the desired square f5. The idea is after }
6... Bf5 { to proceed with } 7. Qf3
{ This was played long ago by the former world champion Tigran Petrosian, and leads to a position for which he, the 9th holder of that title, was extremely well suited.  Note:   7.Qb3  Qb6  8.Bxf6  gxf6  has been played a number of times. }
7... Bg6 8. Bxf6
{ Black's structure is now broken. However, as the f-file is closed, this may not be too serious. Black can now choose whether to trade queens or to keep them on the board. }
8... Qxf6
{ In the famous game Petrosian - Barcza, 1955 Black preferred keeping the queens on the board with   8...gxf6  . The world champion's next move shows impressive positional grasp:  9.Qd1 !  The queen has done her duty and now returns to her starting square, mainly in order to meet ...Qb6 effectively. The game is instructive to such an extent that we've included it in the chapter on model games. }
9. Qxf6 gxf6
{ People used to think this endgame was well playable, but from a number of games, it appeared Black has a tough job in defending his position. Yet, if even strong players like Nigel Short or Vladimir Kramnik - great strategists themselves - see a point in defending this, it can't be so bad. In fact, the struggle very often comes down to whether White can occupy the crucial square f5 with a knight. Petrosian more or less demonstrated how to exchange light-squared bishops and achieve this. In his games, and those of others, a major White plan is the harassment of the Bg6 with an eventual h2-h4, often accompanied by f2-f4. If Black feels forced to trade the bishops, the f5-square will fall into White's hands and strategically the battle is usually already over. Fine examples in which this succeeds are the games Van Wely - Short, 2005 and Grooten - Wade, 2007. It transpired afterwards that Black could have defended themselves much more accurately in both games. For years it was generally understood that Black was slightly worse but had certain well-worked out defences. Then in 2016, Magnus Carlsen's second, Jon-Ludvig Hammer, invented  (on the basis of the position's strategic underpinnings)  the following brilliant novelty, after which even more may be up for grabs for White. The miraculous and bizarre move cooked up at home by Hammer is }
10. Nce2
{ Carlsen used it to beat Kramnik in a splendid game  (in Stavanger, 2016)  and then win the New in Chess prize for Novelty of the Year, which he dedicated to his second ! We discuss the full game later. }
*

