[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview Carlsbad"]
[Black "Overview Carlsbad: 5...Be7 6.e3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7
{ It's about time to start looking at the most played moves in this system. }
6. e3 c6
{ After this move, the basic pawn structure of the Exchange Variation has arisen.  Again, the immediate   6...Bf5  is not possible due to  7.Qb3  , as we've seen before. }
7. Bd3 { Of course, ...Bf5 is prevented when possible. } 7... O-O 8. Qc2 Nbd7
9. Nf3
{ The king's knight's most natural square.  At this moment the knight can be developed to e2 as well:   9.Nge2  . This move opens up 2 additional plans for White, as we've seen already, and therefore maybe the name Carlsbad should be reserved for those cases in which the knight is developed to f3. }
9... Re8 10. O-O Nf8
{ An important moment. White should determine a plan by which to make progress. This position has appeared in the matches of a great many renowned players. }
11. Rab1
{ This is considered to be White's most important idea in this position. He aims at weakening the pawn on c6 by means of b2-b4-b5xc6. By now, we know this plan, the minority attack, is one of the most favorable concepts White can choose in this position.  When I asked club players where White would be best off developing his queens rook, the usual answer was   11.Rac1  . However, the assiduous reader may already know that a different move is better: }
11... a5
{ Black wants to slow down White's minority attack somewhat. On top of that, he wants the a-pawns to be removed from the board. The reason is that if they stay on and White's minority attack continues  (as it will)  , the Black a-pawn could be weak.  Also played is   11...Ne4  with the intention of trading a couple of important pieces.  12.Bxe7  Qxe7  13.Bxe4  dxe4  14.Nd2  Bf5  The e4-pawn has driven away a White knight from the defence, so through this operation we can say that Black has gained space on the kingside, where White's king has barricaded itself. Then, it will be possible to mobilise pieces and attack the White king. Returning to the text: }
12. a3 g6
{ The idea is to trade the white-squared bishops using a time-consuming knight maneuver. Obviously, there are other plans for Black as well, but we'll leave those out of consideration in order that we can form a clear image of the minority attack. }
13. b4 axb4 14. axb4 Ne6
{ Black can also play   14...b5  placing an obstacle in White's path. On the other hand, he'll have weakened his pawn on c6 voluntarily. Now, a major focus of the struggle is Black trying to play a knight to c4. Other problems have already been touched on in the third chapter. }
15. Bh4 Ng7 16. b5 Bf5
{ Black has managed to carry out his plan, but in the meantime, White has made great progress on the other side of the board. }
17. bxc6 bxc6
{ Mission accomplished for White, one could say. Pawn c6 isn't granite anymore, but reduced to rubble. Now White needs to keep it in his sights. }
18. Ne5 Rc8 19. Rb7
{ This kind of progress is usually the byproduct of a successful strategy. Since the rook has free rein on the b-file, it can swing into action in other parts of the board, for instance the 7th rank. A concrete threat has come into existence, namely Bxf6 followed by Nxf7. }
19... Bxd3 20. Qxd3
{ The minority attack has been a success for White. This triumph of the strategy was played in 1950  (!)  by the Dutchman Van den Berg in his game against IM Kramer. White won the game in style, initially playing subtly but before long ending up with extra material. Later the diagram position was reached by others, and in Georgiev-Stavrev 1989, White found an alternative way to secure victory. }
*

