{ After this move, the basic pawn structure of the Exchange Variation has arisen. }
7. Bd3 { Of course, ...Bf5 is prevented when possible. } 7... O-O 8. Qc2 Nbd7
9. Nf3 { The king's knight's most natural square. } 9... Re8 10. O-O Nf8
{ An important moment. White should determine a plan by which to make progress. This position has appeared in the matches of a great many renowned players. }
11. Rab1
{ This is considered to be White's most important idea in this position. He aims at weakening the pawn on c6 by means of b2-b4-b5xc6. By now, we know this plan, the minority attack, is one of the most favorable concepts White can choose in this position. }
11... a5
{ Black wants to slow down White's minority attack somewhat. On top of that, he wants the a-pawns to be removed from the board. The reason is that if they stay on and White's minority attack continues  (as it will)  , the Black a-pawn could be weak. }
12. a3 g6
{ The idea is to trade the white-squared bishops using a time-consuming knight maneuver. Obviously, there are other plans for Black as well, but we'' ll leave those out of consideration in order that we can form a clear image of the minority attack. }
13. b4 axb4 14. axb4 Ne6 15. Bh4 Ng7 16. b5 Bf5
{ Black has managed to carry out his plan, but in the meantime, White has made great progress on the other side of the board. }
17. bxc6 bxc6
{ Mission accomplished for White, one could say. Pawn c6 isn't granite anymore, but reduced to rubble. Now White needs to keep it in his sights. }
18. Ne5 Rc8 19. Rb7
{ This kind of progress is usually the byproduct of a successful strategy. Since the rook has free rein on the b-file, it can swing into action in other parts of the board, for instance the 7th rank. A concrete threat has come into existence, namely Bxf6 followed by Nxf7. }
19... Bxd3 20. Qxd3
{ The minority attack has been a success for White. This triumph of the strategy was played in 1950  (!)  by the Dutchman Van den Berg in his game against IM Kramer. White won the game in style, initially playing subtly but before long ending up with extra material. Later the diagram position was reached by others, and in Georgiev-Stavrev 1989, White found an alternative way to secure victory. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview Rubinstein"]
[Black "Overview Rubinstein"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7 5. e3 O-O 6. Nf3 Nbd7
{ The most neutral move for Black, which was named after Rubinstein. The most important rationale for this move is that Black doesn't know yet how he wants to finish his development. He keeps open the option of the manoeuvre ...Rf8-e8 and ...Nd7-f8, which is typical for this variation. With the text move, White is immediately questioned as to how he should bring his other pieces into play. }
7. Rc1
{ Many who play Black find it hard to fight this rook move. This is because White is keeping his cards close to his chest as well; the rook move is quite useful against almost anything Black does. One of the key problems with Black's game, as we've already seen, is the development of his queen's bishop. It often wants to go to b7, just like in the Tartakower. Perhaps Black even wants to play ...dxc4, but preferably after White has spent a move with his king's bishop first. There will be a mini-game revolving around whether White wants to allow ...dxc4 or would rather alter the structure himself with cxd5. In addition to the played move there are two other ways of playing: 7. Qc2 and 7. Bd3.   7.Qc2  This used to be Kasparov's choice in his younger years. The queen move has roughly the same function as 7. Rc1. White awaits Black's further ideas, but by contrast to the main move, Black has now lost the option to play the freeing ...Ne4 which we know from the Lasker variation. Black has four important possibilities to consider.  c6   7...c5  After this,  8.cxd5  is considered best.  But of course,   8.Rd1  is an idea too.  8...Nxd5  Black wants - as ever - to trade pieces. Moreover, he's currently not in the mood for an isolani on d5.  9.Bxe7  Qxe7  Strangely enough Black - when you wouldn't expect it - allows the isolani. Why ?  Indeed   9...Nxe7  is possible and not necessarily terrible for Black, although, critically, he can't develop much activity for his pieces at this moment.  10.Nxd5  exd5  11.Bd3  g6  12.dxc5  Nxc5  13.O-O  At first sight, one would think White has what he wants. His opponent has an isolated pawn on d5 and two pairs of minor pieces have been traded already. Furthermore, Black has the bad bishop and White's knight has a firm hold on d4. What else would we want ? However, looking at grandmaster praxis, it seems these advantages don't give enough to win. In the databases, there is a preponderance of draws from here.  First we look at   7...h6  which bothers White's bishop on g5 before making a more committal decision. This move was played in the old game Kasparov - Portisch, 1986. White's answer was instructive. Then there are the two c-pawn moves 7... c6 and 7... c5. It's a matter of taste what variation will be chosen. They lead to totally different positions, but have roughly equal popularity. After 7... h6 Kasparov played the shocking  8.cxd5 !?  Portisch believed his opponent, and after  exd5  Of course, the question remains what the great man saw after   8...hxg5  . The play should then continue  9.dxe6  fxe6  10.Nxg5  Nb6  , and then perhaps  11.h4  . My opinion is that White has enough compensation because of Black's weak king position. It's easy to sympathise if Portisch lacked the heart to dive into this quagmire of unclear variations against an attacking legend like Kasparov.  9.Bf4  an interesting fight followed in which Kasparov came out on top.  For a start, the fianchetto with   7...b6  is possible; we omit it from consideration, noting only that there is an obvious similarity with the Tartakower.  8.Rd1  With this rook move - the most popular choice - White discourages a few possible Black pawn thrusts. Here, there is more theory and elite praxis available than usual, since the position can also arise from a Slav. I noticed Kasparov was successful a number of times as White here in simultaneous displays. A very nice game was Kasparov - Amura, 1992.   7.Bd3  This is very straightforward. White develops his last minor piece and prepares castling. The biggest drawback, of course, is that Black can make his opponent lose a tempo after  dxc4  8.Bxc4  Now there are two methods for Black. The other choice Black had on move 8 was:  c5  which is a completely logical advance. Now that White has two pawns in the center and Black only one, Black needs to consciously make an effort to carve out space in the center. We now return to the main move 7. Rc1.  As always, he can opt for the method of   8...a6  with the clear intention of ...b7-b5 followed by ...Bb7. It is best to stop this:  9.a4  Whether White does well by this insertion is not totally clear, and most of the differences are in deep tactical lines. Black usually proceeds from here with:  c5  10.O-O  cxd4  after which White needs to make a major decision. We can see that many grandmasters have a preference for  11.exd4  after which a middle game with an isolated pawn  (for White !)  has arisen. This type of situation usually leads to exciting games. Here the dispute is fierce over whether inserting the moves a4 and a6 benefits White or Black. }
7... c6
{ There's another waiting move analogous to a Black idea in the Queen's Gambit Accepted:   7...a6  . The ability to do this is one of the advantages of a knight on d7 - an idea of which Rubinstein was a supporter. There it supports c5. Hence, at this exact moment White seizes this moment to change the structure with  8.cxd5  After   8.Bd3  Black can free himself with  dxc4  9.Bxc4  b5  10.Bd3  Bb7  as in the aforementioned line. He takes some space on the queenside and is now ready to unravel his center even more through ...c7-c5.  when after  8...exd5  we've suddenly arrived again in the Carlsbad structure. Countless games can be found with this position. A nice example for White is Navara - Apicella, 2013.  Followers of the Tartakower could perhaps wonder whether   7...b6  is also a good option here. A possible continuation is  8.cxd5  exd5  9.Bd3  Bb7  10.O-O  c5  with a position that inherits most of the problems of that lines hanging-pawns feature, without the benefits; therefore we stop the line here. }
8. Bd3 dxc4 9. Bxc4 Nd5
{ This is the the point behind ...c6. Black has defended the d5-square well and is able to play this knight move, trading a couple of minor pieces. The more he can trade, the more Black's position will improve. }
10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. O-O Nxc3
{ This was one of Black's big points. The dark-squared bishop isn't terribly important, but once the knights are traded, Black is better placed to break with ...e6-e5. This idea is taken from the Slav, where the position possesses all the same essential features. The eternal problem of developing Black's Bc8 is now solved, as the bishop can be developed along the diagonal c8-h3. }
12. Rxc3 e5
{ This position illustrates strikingly how Black can overcome his opening problems. A look in the database here will show us that almost everything at the top level ends in a draw. }
