[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview Vienna"]
[Black "Overview Vienna"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3
{ This position is of great importance for all theory. One of the reasons is Black can lure his opponent into this via other move orders, for example via 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3  - an invitation to the Queen's Indian, but Blacks turning it into the Queen's Gambit: d5 4. Nc3 dxc4.  As we've already seen before, a White knight will soon come to f3, which gives soon rise to somewhat different types of positions to those with quick developments of White's bishop to g5. Now that the knight on f6 hasn't been pinned yet, it can do a good job in the lines where Black acts aggressively with }
4... dxc4
{ This variation leads to somewhat obscure positions. Obviously, there are similarities to the Queen's Gambit Accepted, and another possibility is that Black will soon go Bb4, bringing play into the Ragozin. In his book Fundamental Chess Openings, Van der Sterren discusses the modern way of playing the Vienna Variation, which is traditionally the official name of this system. The system was fashionable in the thirties for a while, but then soon sank into oblivion. After 1987 some grandmasters dusted off the system and obtained some remarkable results. In the present day, some world-class players have embraced this provocative way of playing. Among others, the Armenian Levon Aronian beat the Russian Sergey Karjakin with Black by throwing himself full force into the complications. }
5. e4
{ The most principled way, although White is also taking risks. As we'll see, White is forced to sacrifice a pawn later.  After   5.e3  the game transposes to the Queen's Gambit Accepted. }
5... Bb4
{ With this move - also typical for the Ragozin - Black puts pressure on White's center. }
6. Bg5
{ Of course, White plays this counterpin, which prevents ...Nxe4. He's ready for e4-e5 and Bxc4. }
6... c5
{ Black treats this position with a highly sharp countermove in the center. One could wonder whether Black, analogously to the Noteboom, couldn't cling to the pawn on c4:   6...b5  The answer is that this is possible, but leads to irrational complications. The more or less forced follow-up is  7.a4  c6  8.e5  h6  9.exf6  hxg5  10.fxg7  Rg8  In the rapid game Kramnik - Carlsen, 2007 White was victorious after a beautiful piece sacrifice. A better defence for Black was demonstrated in the game Komarov - Naiditsch, 2009. }
7. Bxc4
{ This is the modern approach. White continues his development apace, hoping to make threats against Black's king in turn.  An old and well-trodden variation is   7.e5  cxd4  8.Qa4+  Nc6  9.O-O-O  Bd7  10.Ne4  Be7  11.exf6  gxf6  12.Bh4  . Already long ago we knew Black has enough compensation for the piece. This has been demonstrated in the computer age too, for example in the rapid game Mamedyarov - Van Wely, 2008 in which Black managed to win.  The critical variation now continues: }
7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bxc3+
{ On the immediate   8...Qa5  , White usually responds  9.Bd2  , saving the pawn. }
9. bxc3 Qa5
{ Now White should determine which of his two tactical options promises more. }
10. Bb5+
{ This bishop check has been played most lately.  For a long time   10.Nb5  was played as well, but in the last few years, this line has become abandoned.  Nxe4  is Black's best chance then, when in the fine attacking game Nikolic - Nielsen, 2004 Black succeeded in securing the full point. }
10... Nbd7
{ This answer has been played by almost all elite players.  Not so good is   10...Bd7 ?!  as there now follows  11.Bxf6  gxf6  Certainly not   11...Qxc3+ ??  due to  12.Kf1  gxf6  13.Rc1  Qa5  14.Rc8+  winning material.  12.Qb3  and White appears to have obtained a small edge. In any case, White hasn't sacrificed a pawn so Black has forsaken his king safety in vain.  After the text move, White has to respond to the double threat of ...Nxe4 and ...Qxc3+. He can't parry them both, so he plays }
11. Bxf6 Qxc3+ { Of course, Black takes the pawn with check. } 12. Kf1 gxf6 13.
h4
{ Now that White has also given up his right to castle, he needs to find a way to activate his rook on h1 as quickly as possible. To achieve this, he's hoping to play this rook to the third rank where it can swing in and exploit the weakened position of Black's king. }
13... a6
{ In the game Dreev - Kishnev, 2002 Black proceeded with   13...Qa5  14.Rh3  and now  e5  This is obviously a critical option. After all, doesnt Black simply win a piece ? Dreev had an amazing concept ready:  15.Nf5 !  Qxb5+  (the piece drops with check !)  16.Rd3  and White turned out to have a crushing attack, which culminated soon in victory. The continuation was:  Qb6  17.Rb1  Qa6  18.Kg1 !  Qxa2  19.Rc1  Black can't defend himself against all threats White has waiting in the wings.  b5  20.Rc7  Qa4  21.Qc1  Qa6  22.Rd6  Qxd6  23.Nxd6+  Ke7  24.Rxc8  1-0, Dreev - Kishnev, 2002. }
14. Rh3 { Again, a moment of choice: } 14... Qb4
{ In the past usually   14...Qa5  was played.  In the year 2018, though, the text move has been the one examined, prepared, and tested at the highest level. Without further comment, let us give one example, taken from the Candidates Tournament in Berlin in 2018. There, in Karjakin-Aronian, Black was able to snatch material, retain it despite coming under significant pressure, and win skilfully ! }
15. Rb1 Qd6 16. Be2 Nc5 17. Rc3 Nxe4 18. Rd3 O-O 19. Qc1 Qe5 20. Bf3 f5 21. Qh6
Qf6 22. Qxf6 Nxf6 23. Bxb7 Bxb7 24. Rxb7 Rac8 25. Rg3+ Kh8 26. Rgb3 Ne4
{ The game concluded: } 27. Rb2 Rfd8 28. Nb3 Rd1+ 29. Ke2 Nc3+ 30. Ke3 Kg7 31.
g3 Kf6 32. Ra7 Rc6 33. Kf3 Nb5 34. Ra8 e5 35. Kg2 e4 36. a4 Na3 37. Rd2 Rxd2
38. Nxd2 e3 39. Nf3 Rc2 40. Rxa6+ Kg7 41. Nd4 Rxf2+ 42. Kg1 Nc2 43. Nxc2 Rxc2
44. Kf1 Rf2+ 45. Ke1 Rg2 46. Rb6 Rxg3 47. Rb4 Rg2 48. Rf4 Kg6 49. Rf3 Rg4 50.
Rxe3 Rxa4 51. Kf2 Rxh4 52. Re8 Rg4 53. Kf3 Kg7 54. Re5 Kf6 55. Re8 h5 56. Rh8
