[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Model Games"]
[Result "*"]

{ As a coach, a lot of games come to one’s attention. Most of these arrive on one’s desk through the ‘live transmission’ facility that almost all high-level tournaments offer so that chess aficionados all over the world can follow the progress of games in real time. In addition to this ‘raw data’, it has been recognised in various quarters that the fan experience is enhanced by means of multimedia: an example of this is live video-streams that transmit players’ body language and movements. Additionally, at elite round-robin tournaments, there tends to be live commentary, as well as press conferences after the games. The loser of a game may not want to attend, but in all but the most exceptional circumstances they are obligated to by contract; not to mention, subscribers and sponsors deserve to get some ‘bang for their buck’ as a quid pro quo for the money they pump into the top guys’ prizes.  Over the years I’ve collected a decent number of model games which fulfil almost all the criteria I’ve given earlier in this book. In the last decades, there have been few examples which meet the requirement for an appreciable rating gap  (due to the fact that leading players mostly play against one another)  , however, this is somewhat compensated for by the additional information we are able to obtain about these games from the live media mentioned above, to say nothing of the ‘round summary’ videos or write-ups, or the easy access to annotations by grandmasters. In short: between a variety of different factors and sources, we will manage to fathom the essence of a given meaningful game. Let’s start looking at some of them. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Petrosian, T. vs. Barcza, G."]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6
{ Black would like to develop his bishop on its ideal diagonal  (b1-h7)  . } 6.
e3 Bf5 7. Qf3
{ With this early queen sortie, White can force an ugly weakness in Black's pawn structure. He considers it more important to cause this weakness than to hold on to the bishop pair. }
7... Bg6 8. Bxf6 gxf6
{ The endgame arising after   8...Qxf6  9.Qxf6  gxf6  will be discussed in other games. }
9. Qd1
{ The queen has done her duty and returns at once. The reason for this is Black is ready for ...Qb6, after which the defence of White's b2-pawn would become a problem. }
9... Qb6 10. Qd2 Na6 11. Nf3 O-O-O
{ There is always some doubt about where Black should leave his king. Neither the kingside nor the center is appealing, but it won't find shelter on the queenside either. }
12. a3
{ A thematic move. Not only does it deprive the Black pieces of an outpost on b4, but also White can start the minority attack later through b2-b4. Also important is that by playing b2-b4, possible counter-chances with ...c6-c5 can be discounted in future calculations. }
12... Nc7
{ Here   12...c5 ?!  fails to  13.Na4  Qc6  14.Nxc5  Nxc5  15.dxc5  and Black can't take back on c5 because of the deadly pin on c-file. }
13. b4 Ne8 14. Be2 Nd6 15. Qa2 Ne4 16. Rc1 Nxc3 17. Rxc3 Bd6 18. O-O Kd7
{ The king leaves the line of fire. Time for White to formulate a new plan. }
19. Nh4 { White's idea will soon become clear. } 19... Ke7 20. f4
{ The discerning reader may well assess that with this move White voluntarily weakens his pawn formation. In playing this, indeed, he saddles himself with a weak e3-pawn on a half-open file. But Petrosian reckons that Black, with his current piece configuration, is hardly able to attack this weakness. With his last move White aims to trade the light-square bishops. After this exchange, the advantages become obvious, since White will:   - get the mighty square f5 for his knight.   - have eliminated Blacks bishop pair.   - have made Black's pawns on the kingside very vulnerable. }
20... Be4 21. Bd3 Bxd3
{ There isn't a choice; on g6 the bishop would be trapped, and letting White take on e4 is likely even worse. }
22. Rxd3 Rd7 23. Nf5+
{ The knight has landed on its ideal square, and has undisputed dominion over all it surveys. }
23... Kd8 24. Rb1 a6
{ Black tries to dig in and prepare himself for the coming White breakthrough. Yet Petrosian is a true master in exploiting these kinds of advantages. He starts as it were to 'massage' his opponent's structure and weaknesses. In the long run, he wants to play b4-b5, but in the meantime, he's also watching the weak pawns on the kingside. }
25. Qf2 Re8 26. Rdb3 Qb5 27. Rc3 Bf8 28. Qc2 Qb6 29. Rcb3 Qb5 30. Kf2
{ Making it even clearer that Black will never develop any play against e3. }
30... Rc7 31. Rc3 a5
{ Black loses all patience, though this plays into White's hands. } 32. Rcb3
Qc4 33. Qb2
{ Funnily enough, Petrosian prefers on this occasion to convert with queens still on. }
33... axb4 34. axb4 Kd7 35. Ra1 Rcc8 36. Ra7 Qb5 37. Qa3 Rc7 38. Ng3 Rec8 39.
Qb2 Qc4 40. Qb1
{ Another short move. From her new throne the queen surveys the Black kingside. There is still no concrete threat, but everything is very unpleasant for Black. }
40... Ke8 41. Nh5 Bd6
{ Black just gives something away, as he is at his wit's end.  After a move like   41...Be7  ,  42.Rb2  h6  43.Qh7 !  is very strong.  Qc3  44.Raa2  Qc4  45.Qg8+  and White wins at least a pawn. }
42. b5 { Finally, the long-expected advance has come. } 42... b6
{ This doesn't help, but Black has no more sensible ideas left. White can now start cleaning up !   42...c5  is met by  43.b6 !  Re7  44.Nxf6+  Kd8  and White can now conclude the game by  45.Qxh7 !  Qxb3  46.Qg8+  Re8  47.Qxe8# }
43. Ra2 cxb5 44. Rxb5 Be7 45. Rxb6 Rc6 46. Rxc6 Rxc6 47. Ra8+ Kd7 48. Ra7+ Rc7
49. Rxc7+ Kxc7 50. Qxh7
{ White has seized two pawns. No counterplay is possible, and the finish was clinical. }
50... Qa2+ 51. Kf3 Qd2 52. Qb1 f5 53. Ng3 Bh4 54. Ne2 Be7 55. h3 Bb4 56. Ng3
Kc6 57. Nxf5 Kb5 58. Nd6+ Ka4 59. Nxf7 Ba3 60. Ne5
{ Now four pawns down, Barcza decided he had suffered enough. } *

