1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. Qf3
{ We have just seen the moves up to this point in the previous classic game. }
7... Bg6 8. Bxf6
{ In this way, Black's pawn formation is compromised in exchange for the bishop pair. }
8... Qxf6
{ Short firmly believes Black can defend this endgame without the presence of queens. Personally, I have never understood what players see in this as Black. }
9. Qxf6 gxf6
{ Here we reach the position on which opinions are so divided. Black accepts the ugly doubled pawns in exchange for the bishop pair. }
10. Nf3 Nd7 11. Nh4 Be7 12. g3 Nb6 13. f3 a5 14. Kf2 a4 15. Rc1 Nc8 16. Be2 Nd6
17. Rhd1 O-O 18. Bd3 Rfe8
{ This nonchalant move will get Black into trouble.  He should have played   18...Bxd3  19.Rxd3  f5  , although White is still better then. In the game, White obtains a strong grip on the f5-square. If Black plays f5 himself, then the cost of losing the square becomes that much greater. }
19. g4 Bf8 20. Ne2 { The knight is on its way to f5. } 20... Bh6 21. f4
{ White doesn't object to giving up the e4-outpost. The one on f5 is much more important. }
21... Bxd3 22. Rxd3
{ Black has lost the bishop pair and is now stuck with a weak square on f5 and a bishop that has no greater value than the wood of which it is formed. }
22... Bf8 23. Ng3 Ra5 24. Rc2 Rb5 25. Nhf5 Nc4
{ Black can't trade knights because then he would end up in a hopeless situation of a good White knight versus a helpless Black bishop. }
26. b3 axb3 27. Rxb3
{ White would like to trade off the last Black piece which is more active than its counterpart, before commencing decisive actions on the kingside. }
27... Rxb3
{ Perhaps Black could have played a little differently with, say,   27...h6  28.Rxb5  cxb5  , although the position is still miserable. }
28. axb3 Na5 29. Nh5 { Stretching Black's defences. } 29... Re6
{ Forced, since otherwise Black would lose a pawn for free. } 30. Ra2
{ But now that the back rank has been mortally weakened, White immediately uses it. }
30... b6
{ After   30...Nxb3  , there follows  31.Ra8  and the threat of Nh6+ will cost Black decisive material:  h6  32.Nxh6+  Kh7  33.Rxf8  Kxh6  34.Rh8+  Kg6  35.f5+  . }
31. Ra4
{ Nothing can be done about the threat of b3-b4, so Black admitted defeat. } *

