[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Grooten, H. vs. Wade, R."]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 h6 7. Bh4 Bf5 8. Qf3
Bh7 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. Qxf6 gxf6
{ The same sort of position has arisen as in the last game, with Black having inserted the two extra  (but rather useless)  moves ...h6 and ...Bh7. }
11. Nf3 Nd7 12. O-O-O Bb4 13. Bd3
{ White opts for the same plan again. He wants to trade the light-square bishops in order to secure an outpost on f5  (and sometimes also h5)  for his knight  (s)  . }
13... O-O
{ Black immediately gives White what he's looking for, without making his opponent spend time or effort on it.  More resistance was offered with   13...Bg6  , whereupon White can also seize square f5 after  14.Nh4  Rg8  15.Ne2  followed by Ne2-g3. Also sometimes useful is the manoeuvre of the second knight to f4 instead of g3. }
14. Bxh7+ Kxh7 15. Ne2 Rac8
{ It was too late to try and control the f5-square by means of   15...f5 ?  since after  16.Nh4  , the pawn is lost together with the square it is on. }
16. Kb1 Rg8 17. Nh4 Rg4 18. g3
{ This pawn occupies a square which White would often like to use for a knight, so this couple of moves can be counted as a minor success for Black. }
18... Nf8 19. a3 Ba5 20. h3 Rg8 21. Nf5
{ From here on in, the knights get to stir up chaos within Black's camp at will. }
21... Re8 22. Nf4 Bd8 { Black is limited to passive defence. } 23. Nh5 Re6 24.
g4
{ The knights have been stabilized on the white squares.  A little more direct was   24.Rd3 ! }
24... Ng6 25. Rd3 Ne7 { Black tries to at least get rid of one knight. } 26.
Rb3 b6
{ Black's problem is that after the trade of the knight on f5 by   26...Nxf5  27.gxf5  he loses the b7-pawn; it can't be defended by  Re7  due to  28.Nxf6+  . }
27. Nf4 Re4 { 27...Nxf5  28.Nxe6  Nd6  29.Nf4  is similar. } 28. Ng3
{ The exchange down in a worse position, my veteran opponent had seen enough. }
*

