[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Carlsen, M. vs. Kramnik, V."]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. Qf3 Bg6 8.
Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Qxf6 gxf6 10. Nf3 Nd7 11. Nh4 Be7
{ A very well-known position, in which Carlsen introduces a formidable novelty. }
12. Ne2
{ On the face of it a very strange move, but extremely strong ! From previous games, we can see that the White knights aren't shy about moving to the kingside. But Carlsen demonstrates in this game that they can go there without any delay at all. }
12... Nb6 { White doesn't mind   12...Bb4+  13.Kd1  . } 13. Ng3 Bb4+ 14. Kd1
Na4 15. Ngf5
{ Thus White gains control over square f5 with his knights, even without having to trade the light-square bishop. }
15... Kd7
{ 15...Nxb2+  is not possible because of queenside structural issues:  16.Kc2  Nc4  17.Bxc4  dxc4  18.Rhb1  c5   18...Ba5  19.Rxb7  19.a3  Ba5  20.Rxb7  cxd4  21.exd4  O-O  22.Nxg6  hxg6  23.Ne7+  Kg7  24.Nc6  and White has an overwhelming position. }
16. Rb1 Ke6 17. Bd3 Rhc8 18. Ke2
{ White has restored normalcy to the rest of his position, leaving the gains made by his knights beyond dispute. }
18... Bf8 19. g4
{ This typical move reinforces the f5-knight definitively against any challenge. }
19... c5
{ Kramnik prefers to play actively, but this proved impossible to do without creating more weaknesses. }
20. Ng2 cxd4 21. exd4 Bd6 22. h4 h5
{ This comes at a cost,  though   22...Rh8  23.Kf3 !  is no picnic either. }
23. Ng7+ Ke7 24. gxh5 Bxd3+ 25. Kxd3
{ White has succeeded again in trading the light-squared bishops and still dominates f5, which is the most important theme in this position. Strategically, he is already winning. This, naturally, manifests itself through his h-pawns, which are doubled, and passed - and one is extra, as Ivan Sokolov would say ! }
25... Kd7 26. Ne3 Nb6 27. Ng4 Rh8 28. Rhe1
{ There is no need to take on f6,  but also no need to reject the free pawn:   28.Nxf6+  Ke7  29.Ng4  is equally winning }
28... Be7 29. Nf5 Bd8 30. h6
{ Carlsen knows the front h-pawn will bring home the bacon. } 30... Rc8 31. b3
Rc6 32. Nge3 Bc7 33. Rbc1 Rxc1 34. Rxc1 Bf4 35. Rc5 Ke6 36. Ng7+ Kd6 37. Ng4
Nd7 38. Rc2 f5 { A death rattle. } 39. Nxf5+ Ke6 40. Ng7+ Kd6 41. Re2 Kc6 42.
Re8 { Carlsen finishes his job efficiently. } 42... Rxe8 43. Nxe8 Nf8 44. Ne5+
Bxe5 45. dxe5 Kd7 46. Nf6+ Ke6 47. h5 Kxe5 48. Nd7+
{ A flourish, sometimes referred to as chessplayer humour. } 48... Nxd7 49. h7
Nc5+ 50. Ke2 *

