[Black "Anand, V. vs. Ljubojevic, L."]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7 5. e3 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. Nf3 b6 8. Rc1
Bb7 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. b4 a6 12. Be2 Re8 13. O-O Nd7 14. Qb3 Nf8
15. Rfd1 Qd6 16. b5 a5 17. Bf1 Rad8 18. g3 h5 19. Bg2 h4 20. Ne2 hxg3 21. hxg3
Ne6 22. Nf4 Ng5 23. Rc2 Nxf3+ 24. Bxf3 Bg5 25. Ne2 g6 26. Rdc1 Rd7 27. Rc3 Kg7
28. Qc2 Bd8 29. Nf4 Rh8 30. Qd3 Rh6 31. a3 Re7 32. Bg2 Re8 33. Qd1 Reh8 34. Nd3
Qd7 35. a4 Rh2 36. Qf3 Qe6
{ After a long manoeuvring game in which all of White's pieces have basically reached their ideal squares, we've reached a position where White needs to decide how to break through. It is important to realise just how deceptive Black's h-file activity is: with the White bishop entrenched on g2, the rooks will accomplish nothing. }
37. Ne5
{ Strong,  but better was   37.Rxc7 !  Bxc7  38.Rxc7  Bc8  39.Ne5  Rxg2+  40.Kxg2  Rf8  41.g4  and Black is helpless. }
37... R2h5
{ Similarly, after   37...R2h7  , White can take his chance by means of  38.Rxc7 !  Bxc7  39.Rxc7  Kg8  and now:  Correct is  40.Nc6 !  Certainly not   40.Rxb7 ?  because of  Qc8 !  which is a double threat - of mate as well as the rook - for instance, see the line  41.Rxf7   41.Qxf7+  Rxf7  42.Rxf7  is the bail-out White needs.  41...Rh1+ !  42.Bxh1  Qc1+  43.Kg2  Qxh1#  40...Bxc6  41.Rxc6  Qe7  42.Qxd5  and White is winning. }
38. Qxf7+ { Beautiful from Anand. } 38... Qxf7 39. Nxf7 Kxf7 40. Rxc7+ Bxc7 41.
Rxc7+ Kf6 42. Rxb7
{ White already has two pawns for the exchange, and more are about to fall. In addition to this, Black's rooks are still standing to attention on the h-file, hoping against hope to deliver mate on h1. Round this off with a huge structural plus and we can conclude that White is winning. }
42... Rc8 43. Rxb6+ Kf7 44. Bf3 Rc1+ 45. Kg2 Rhh1 46. Bxd5+ Kg7 47. Rb7+ Kh6
48. Kf3 Rh2 49. b6 Rc2 50. Rb8 Rhxf2+ 51. Kg4 Rf5 52. b7 *

