[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Karpov, A. vs. Georgiev, K."]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 8. Be2
Bb7 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. b4 c6
{ Black avoids the simplification of the position by   11...c5  and aims instead for a long middlegame in which he can try to regroup his minor pieces behind a wall of pawns. }
12. O-O Qd6 13. Qb3 Nd7
{ White mainly has two basic plans:   - Play in the center. Preparing and pushing through the advance e3-e4.   - Play down the c-file, with emphasis on c6. }
14. Rfe1 { Indicating White's use of the first plan. } 14... Be7
{ 14...a5  15.bxa5  Rxa5  16.a4  Bd8  17.Bf1  Nf6  18.g3  Bc7 = } 15. Rab1 a5
{ Black tries to start counterplay on the queenside, but it's possible he should have been more patient. The moment is instructive, because both sides have structures that could also arise from other openings - for example, the Queen's Indian. }
16. bxa5
{ This counter-intuitive trade gives White an advantage.  After   16.b5  , Black responds with  c5 !  with a good game.  Worse still is   16.a3  on account of  axb4  17.axb4  b5 !  when Black executes the manoeuvre ...Nd7-b6-c4, after which he can deal with his bad bishop and begin playing to win. }
16... Rxa5 17. a4 { Too early is   17.e4  Ra3  18.Qc2  dxe4  19.Nxe4  Qf4 = }
17... Re8 18. Bf1
{ Again, its not a good time for   18.e4  dxe4  19.Nxe4   19.Bc4 ?!  exf3  20.Bxf7+  Kf8  21.Bxe8  Kxe8  22.Qg8+  Nf8  ∓  19...Qg6  ∞  with counterplay. }
18... Bf8
{ The possibility of   18...Ba6  was indicated by Ftacnik, and in spite of the further weakening of c6, I suspect Black should have done this and traded off his bad bishop. }
19. Qc2
{ Karpov is preparing the eventual central pawn thrust very carefully.  Again, the possibility of   19.e4  can be considered, but it doesn't give the desired results. After  dxe4  20.Nxe4  , Black has the answer  Qa3 !  and his position holds firm.  Not, though,   20...Qf4  due to  21.g3 !  Qb8  22.Bc4  . }
19... g6 20. e4 { The time is now ripe. } 20... dxe4 21. Nxe4 Qf4 22. Bc4
{ This is the idea. Blacks 19th move turned his g-pawn into a potential target. }
22... Bg7
{ Much better was the escape attempt with   22...c5  23.Ng3  Also   23.Neg5  doesnt give much after  Rxe1+  24.Rxe1  Kg7  25.Bxf7  Qf5  .  23...Rxe1+  24.Rxe1  Kg7  and it seems Black can survive. }
23. Re2
{ Too timid. Karpov misses an excellent possibility by which he could have gained complete control of the game.  White now had   23.Nh4 !!  , a spectacular master-stroke conferring a large advantage on him, as  Qxh4  is met by  24.Bxf7+  Kxf7  25.Nd6+  Kg8  26.Rxe8+  . }
23... c5
{ 23...Rea8  24.Bb3  Nf6  25.Ne5 !  ±     23...b5  was reasonable:  24.Bb3  += }
24. d5 Raa8
{ 24...Rea8 !?  25.Bb3  Ne5  26.Nxe5  Bxe5  ⇆  with counterplay was also an option. }
25. Rbe1 Rad8
{ And here it would have been better to trade some pieces with   25...Ne5  26.Nxe5  Rxe5  . }
26. Qb3 { Eyeing f7, but also keeping various a5 ideas in mind. } 26... Ba8 27.
g3 Qb8
{ Also   27...Qg4  won't help Black after  28.h3 !  Qh5   28...Qxh3 ?  29.Neg5 !  +-  with the double threat of Rxe8 and Nxh3.  29.Kg2  ± }
28. d6 { Opening the a2-g8 diagonal. } 28... Rf8
{ Capitulation.  A nice variation occurs after   28...Rxe4  29.Bxf7+  Kh7  30.Rxe4  Bxe4  31.Rxe4  Nf6  and now the nice  Relatively better yet also losing is   31...Nf8  32.Qe3  Qxd6  33.Bc4  32.Bxg6+ !!  Kxg6  33.Re7  Kh7   33...Ne8  34.Qc2+  Kf6  35.Qc4  Kg6  36.Qe4+  Kf6  37.Qe6#  34.Qd3+  Kg8  35.Qg6  Ne8  36.d7  +-  The only chance was   28...Ne5  , although after  29.Nxe5  Rxe5  30.Bxf7+  Kh7  , White still has a nearly decisive advantage after  31.Qc2 ! }
29. Bxf7+ { Brilliantly seen by Karpov. } 29... Rxf7 30. Neg5 hxg5 31. Nxg5 Rf8
{ Or   31...Qxd6  32.Qxf7+  Kh8  33.Re7  Rg8  34.Rxd7  Qc6  35.Qxg7+ !  Rxg7  36.Re8+  Rg8  37.Rh7# }
32. Re8
{ Not   32.Nxf7 ?  because of  Qb7 !  and Black defends himself succesfully. }
32... Qxd6
{ 32...Qb7  (Ftacnik)  33.Qxf7+  Kh8  34.Rxa8  Qxa8  35.Qxg6  Nf6  36.Re7  +- }
33. Qxf7+ Kh8 34. Ne6 *

