[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Fischer, R.J. vs. Spassky, B."]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d4 Nf6 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bg5 O-O 6. e3 h6 7. Bh4 b6 8. cxd5
Nxd5 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Nxd5 exd5 11. Rc1 Be6 12. Qa4 c5 13. Qa3 Rc8 14. Bb5 a6
{ One alternative is   14...Kf8  with the intention of doing something about the pin. Black is now ready for ...c5-c4 followed by ...a7-a6 and ...b6-b5.  Another idea is   14...Qb7  , which also intends ...c5-c4. }
15. dxc5 { White decides to cause his opponent hanging pawns. } 15... bxc5 16.
O-O Ra7 { Geller said afterward that   16...Qb7  was preferable. } 17. Be2 Nd7
{ Black is stuck with hanging pawns. The pin on the a3-f8 diagonal is henceforth a little bothersome in that respect, preventing both possible thrusts. Although it's not clear yet how White poses his next questions, it's clear most of his pieces  (except for Rf1)  are more active than the Black equivalents.  By the way, Spassky could have neutralized the pin by   17...c4  , but this would have come at the expense of the d4-square. One continuation then is  18.Qxe7  Rxe7  19.Nd4  Nc6  , as indicated by Tal.  20.Nxe6  fxe6  21.b3  Na5  22.bxc4  Nxc4  , when White seems to nevertheless have a fair edge. He has a much better pawn structure and the advantage of a bishop versus a knight in a position with pawns on both wings. }
18. Nd4
{ Fischer would not be Fischer if he didnt have a special insight into this position. White aims at trading Black's bishop by means of Nd4xe6. This seems paradoxical at first, since it both helps Black to get rid of his prospectless bishop and strengthening Black's pawn structure. However, this is a typical case in which we are well advised to pay attention to that which remains on the board, not what leaves it. It turns out that White's major pieces work well with the bishop, and that he will have a large advantage in coordination. }
18... Qf8
{ This move was greatly criticized afterward, and supports the conclusion that Spassky didn't show his best chess in this match.  In Reykjavik, commentators indicated Spassky should have proceeded with   18...Nf6  . However, it's clear that White can gain an edge through the similar continuation  19.Nxe6  fxe6  , after which he can increase pressure on pawn c5 by  20.Rc2  .  After the text move, though, Fischer made a decision that was considered highly remarkable by theoreticians at that time: }
19. Nxe6 fxe6 20. e4
{ The point which White has been preparing. Blacks seemingly strengthened pawn structure is being attacked. Hanging pawns aren't called hanging pawns for no reason ! }
20... d4
{ A suboptimal defence by Spassky.  The question mark was originally given by Kasparov in My Great Predecessors part IV.  With this move, Black gives away the important c4-square, of which White's bishop can now make clever use.  Perhaps Black should have answered   20...Rc6 !?  , a possibility that contemporary annotators didn't consider. White stands better, but the rook would have defended Black's pawns along the 6th rank well. }
21. f4
{ Now that White has a pawn majority on the kingside, he begins pushing it. }
21... Qe7 { 21...Kh8  seems more flexible. } 22. e5
{ White fixes Black's e6-pawn on a white square, making it a target even while increasing his spatial advantage and minimising the range of Black's knight. Had Fischer allowed e5, the risk of counterplay would have been higher. }
22... Rb8 { For a specific reason, the rook doesn't stand so well here. } 23.
Bc4 Kh8
{ Since Black has placed his rook on b8, the strong bishop on c4 can't be driven away by   23...Nb6  , as White then would have the strong  24.Qb3 ! }
24. Qh3 { A nice switch to the kingside, which is White's next project. } 24...
Nf8
{ The knight finds itself very passively situated, and now White can take his own time to prepare a hammer blow.  Grabbing on b2 was Blacks best chance of survival. After   24...Rxb2  25.Bxe6  Rc7  26.Bd5  , White has an excellent position, but there still remains some work to do, notwithstanding White's strong central pawns. }
25. b3 { 25.Rc2  was strong as well. } 25... a5 26. f5
{ Opening files and diagonals on the kingside, so that White's pieces can reach new levels of activity there. }
26... exf5 27. Rxf5 Nh7 28. Rcf1 { Not   28.Rf7 ??  because of  Ng5  . } 28...
Qd8 29. Qg3
{ White's pieces have become coordinated into an imposing attacking unit. In their next mission, they are joined by the passed pawn on the e-file, which plays an important part in the expansion of White's strategic advantage. }
29... Rbb7 30. h4 Re7 31. e6
{ White can afford to loosen his grip on f6, since ...Nf6 is almost always answered with an exchange sacrifice. }
31... Rac7 32. Qe5 Qe8
{ If Black had tried to get active by means of   32...d3  , then according to Timman  33.R5f3 !  would quickly put paid to that particular ambition. }
33. a4
{ Another classic Fischer move. His pieces are so dominant that Black can't do anything. This move restricts Black's position, and at the same time drives home to his opponent, on a psychological level, just how poor the position's prospects are. }
33... Qd8 34. R1f2 Qe8 35. R2f3 Qd8 36. Bd3
{ Fischer decides to form a battery on the b1-h7 diagonal with the queen and bishop.  Very strong now was   36.Rh5  with the threat of Rxh6. After  Kg8  37.Rg3  , the curtain falls because Rxh6 can't be parried. }
36... Qe8 37. Qe4 { The deadly threat is 38. Rf8+ and Black gets mated. } 37...
Nf6
{ Of course,   37...Rxe6  had to be calculated. After  38.Rf8+ !  Nxf8  39.Rxf8+  Qxf8  40.Qh7#  it's mate ! }
38. Rxf6 { This isn't so hard anymore now. } 38... gxf6 39. Rxf6 Kg8 40. Bc4
Kh8 41. Qf4 { Mate is now forced, so Spassky resigned. } *

