[Black "Andersson, U. vs. Nunn, J."]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. d4 c5 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8.
dxc5 Bxc5 9. Bg5 O-O 10. Nc3 d4 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. Nd5 Qd8 13. Nd2 a6
{ Although White has opted to give up the bishop pair, his remaining pieces stand strongly. The bishop on g2 has a nice diagonal and both White knights can find nice homes in the center  (d5, c4, d3, f4)  . The isolated pawn on d4 can be blocked well with a knight on d3, which would also restrict the activity of Black's dark-squared bishop. White is slightly better. }
14. Rc1 Ba7 15. Re1 Re8
{ After   15...Bf5  , a natural continuation would be  16.Qb3  Rb8  Better than   16...Qd7 ?!  17.Nb6  Bxb6  18.Qxb6  and White exerts pressure both over the c-file and the long diagonal.  17.Nc4  Be6  After   17...b5 ?!  , White has a tactical shot:  18.Nd6 !  Qxd6  19.Rxc6  and he secures the c-file.  18.e4  and it appears this position is playable for Black. }
16. Nf4 Bd7 17. Qb3 Rb8 18. Qd5
{ A strong move. By centralizing the queen, White disrupts the harmony between his opponent's pieces. }
18... Rc8
{ It's actually quite hard to get rid of the marauding queen, e.g.   18...Re5  19.Qd6  Rc8  20.Nc4  Bb8  21.Qa3  Re8  22.Nd6  Bxd6  23.Qxd6  and White is better. }
19. Nc4 Bb8 20. Nd3 Qc7 21. Qc5 Rcd8 22. Bf3 h6 23. b4 Ba7 24. Qd6 Qc8
{ Black has to avoid the trade of queens, but in doing so, he makes other concessions. }
25. Na5
{ Increasing the pressure on the weak point c6. Black needs to worry constantly about captures on b7 and c6. }
25... Be6 { 25...Bb8  26.Qc5  Ba7  27.Qh5  is also good for White. } 26. Qf4
Bd5 27. Bxd5 Rxd5 28. Qf3
{ White could also have increased the pressure on c6 by means of   28.Rc4  . }
28... Red8 { Tougher was   28...Rd6 } 29. Rc4 Qd7 30. Nxc6
{ The positional decision. Black's pawn structure on the queenside is shattered, while hes also stuck with a bad bishop versus a superior white knight.  Andersson was sometimes reluctant to seek out combinations in the final conversion of an edge. This was already possible here with   30.Nxb7 !  Qxb7  31.Rec1  and any knight move will lose to Rc7. White will then win back the material, plus interest. }
30... bxc6 31. Rec1 Rc8 32. R1c2 Bb8
{ This mistake precipitates the end. Square c5 is now accessible to a knight. The rest can be trusted to Andersson.  The only chance for Nunn to keep on fighting was   32...a5  33.bxa5  Rxa5  . }
33. Nc5 Qd6 34. Qa3 Re8 35. Nd3 { 35.Qxa6  at once was allowed too. } 35... a5
36. Rxc6 Qe7 37. Qb3 Rh5 38. Rc8 axb4 39. Qxb4 { Black resigned. } *

