[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Sadler, M. vs. Krasenkow, M."]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c6 4. Nf3 dxc4 5. a4 Bb4 6. e3 b5 7. Bd2 a5 8. axb5
Bxc3 9. Bxc3
{ It's possible for White to opt for a pawn sacrifice after   9.bxc3 !?  cxb5  10.Ne5  , but the compensation looks weak. }
9... cxb5 10. b3 Bb7 11. bxc4
{ White has another aggressive possibility in   11.d5 !?  . After  Nf6  12.bxc4  b4  , White should give up the bishop pair in order not to lose time:  13.Bxf6  Qxf6  14.Qa4+  Nd7  but practice has shown he then doesn't have much. }
11... b4 12. Bb2 Nf6 13. Bd3 Nbd7
{ It would be a misconception to eliminate White's bishop by means of   13...Be4 ?!  As well as losing time, this bishop trade takes away a necessary defender of Black's queenside pawns.  14.Bxe4  Nxe4  15.Qc2  Nf6  16.O-O  Nbd7  17.c5  and White stands better. }
14. O-O O-O
{ We can see the contours of a thematic Noteboom battle in all its glory ! White has a strong pawn mass in the center, while Black has two connected passed pawns on the queenside. A fascinating fight has been set into motion ! The question is, of course, whether White's center supported by the bishop pair is worth more, or Black's perilous pawn duo on the queenside ?! }
15. Re1
{ One of the main continuations. White has two alternatives:  A rather older way of playing is   15.Qc2  , simply continuing development.  After   15.Nd2  , White is ready for f2-f4, permanently cutting out Black's idea of ...e6-e5, and preparing to steamroll Black with e3-e4 and possibly e4-e5 and f4-f5. Therefore, the answer is more or less forced:  e5  16.Re1   16.f4  exd4  17.exd4  Qb6  is reasonable for Black.  16...Qc7  and for the time being, the position seems to be well-balanced. }
15... Ne4
{ Krasenkow decides, naturally enough, to stop e3-e4, even though many others have have chosen otherwise. The Polish grandmaster gives a good example in this game of how to block White's center pawns. }
16. Nd2
{ Sadler wants to get rid of the bothersome Ne4 as soon as possible.   16.Qc2  f5 !  doesn't solve this central problem of White's. }
16... Nxd2 17. Qxd2 Qc7 18. c5
{ This was a novelty at that time.  Now, on   18.e4 ?!  , the thematic  e5 !  would follow. }
18... f5 { Here,   18...e5 ?!  would not be quite as good. } 19. f3
{ The seemingly appealing   19.e4 !?  is countered as follows:  fxe4  20.Bxe4  Bd5 !  and Black has achieved his blockade on the light squares. }
19... Nf6 20. Bc4
{ Too early is   20.e4 ?!  because of  fxe4  21.fxe4  Ng4  22.g3  Rf3 !  Black gets a decisive initiative on the kingside. }
20... Bd5 21. Bxd5
{ Worse is   21.Bd3  because Black could improve the bishop's position with  Bc6 ! }
21... Nxd5
{ More consistent with the strategy Black has been adopting is   21...exd5  . This sidelines the Bb2 for a while. Yet after  22.Ra4  , possibly followed by Qd2-c2-b3, Black's pawns have been blocked while the bishop can be maneuvered to g3 via c1-d2-e1, after which things aren't that bad for White. }
22. e4
{ This logical advance is not without its dangers for White.  Preferable was   22.Ra4  . }
22... fxe4 23. fxe4 Nf6 24. h3
{ This costs time, but White wanted to eliminate the threat of ...Ng4.  The problem is that   24.d5  is met by  Ng4 !  and White is in trouble.   24...Qxc5+  25.Bd4  Qb5  was also an option for Black.  White could eliminate the threat of ... Ng4 by playing   24.Qd1 !?  and at the same time, he keeps an eye on a4 so that Black can't advance with his pawns too quickly. }
24... Qc6 { Hindering White's d4-d5 idea. } 25. Qd3
{ White wants to protect e4 obviously, but now Black can set his queenside pawns into motion.  He should have tried   25.d5 !?  , regardless of whether it works, by elimination. After  Qxc5+   25...exd5  26.Bxf6  Rxf6  runs into  27.Qxd5+  , possibly followed by Reb1, and Black's pawns are vulnerable.  26.Bd4  Qe7  27.d6 !  White has developed some counterplay. He has managed to activate his bishop and has a far-advanced passed pawn at his disposal as well. However, Black's chances should still be rated higher: he is a pawn up and his queenside pawns have remained intact. }
25... a4 26. d5 { White employs the pawn sacrifice: better late than never. }
26... exd5 27. Bxf6 Qxf6 28. Qxd5+
{ After   28.exd5 ?  Qf2+  29.Kh1  b3 !  , all of Blacks pawns are too dangerous. }
28... Qf7 29. c6 b3
{ Now this is a tactical free-for-all, but Black's passed pawns are more dangerous as they are connected. }
30. c7
{ The passive   30.Reb1  was probably better.  After   30.Rf1  , Black wins thus:  Qxd5  31.exd5  b2  32.Rxf8+  Kxf8  33.Rf1+  Ke7  and his pawns walk home. }
30... Rfc8 31. Rac1 b2 { White's position is beyond saving. } 32. Qxa8
{ A nice try, even though White is lost in any case.  The pawns also reach the other side after   32.Rc6  Qxd5  33.exd5  a3  . }
32... Rxa8 33. c8=Q+ Rxc8 34. Rxc8+ Qf8 35. Rxf8+ Kxf8 36. Rb1 a3
{ A position typical of Black wins in the Noteboom ! } 37. Kf2 Ke7 38. Ke3 a2
39. Rxb2 a1=Q *

