[Black "Kasparov, G. vs. Sosonko, G."]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 h6 7. Bh4 c5 8. e3
g5 9. Bg3 Ne4 10. Bb5+ Kf8
{ We have already discussed the back-story behind this move, which seemingly presents White with great tactical problems, related to both the a5-e1 diagonal and the b5-bishop. More subtly, Black often wants to play ...Bxc3, bxc3 c4 in order to exploit his majority on the queenside. White's bishops would then be very poorly placed. However, Kasparov had a formidable novelty in mind for this game.  The main line is   10...Bd7  11.Bxd7+  Nxd7  12.O-O  , which is playable for Black. }
11. dxc5
{ This move, offering an exchange sacrifice, initiates a very clever concept by which White solves the issues in his position.  It is known that   11.O-O  isn't so good on account of  Bxc3  12.bxc3  c4 !  and White is doing badly. }
11... Nxc3
{ After   11...Qa5  , there follows  12.Qd4  Kg8   12...Bxc3+  13.bxc3  ;  if Black instead plays   12...Rg8  13.O-O  Bxc3  , White can sacrifice a piece with  14.Qxd5 !  , which grants him a large advantage after  Qxb5  15.Qxe4  because the threat of Bd6+ combined with Qh7 is highly irritating for Black.  13.Be5 !  and White gains control. }
12. bxc3 Bxc3+ 13. Ke2 Bxa1 14. Qxa1
{ White has a tremendous amount of compensation, as discussed before. The position heavily favours bishops over knights, and even over rooks. }
14... f6
{ The best defence. Black is weak on the dark squares and this move at least tries to get back some control over them.  After   14...Kg8  15.Be5  Rh7  16.Bf6  Qa5  17.Bd3  , White is already winning. }
15. h4
{ A very handy move to have, trying to prise open the position and obtain more squares for the White pieces.  Also worthy of consideration was the immediate   15.Rd1  with  Kg7  16.Bc4  Be6  17.Qb2  as a possible continuation; Black has big issues here too. }
15... g4
{ Logically, Black tries to keep the lines closed.  But   15...Kg7  should have been preferred, after which things aren't that clear according to Kasparov. Personally, I think White still has wonderful compensation. }
16. Nd4 Kf7 17. Bd3
{ A very smart move. There are two purposes:   - b5 is being cleared for the knight, which can soon join the battle via d6.   - By playing h5 White can create an outpost for his bishop on g6, after which a mating net is beginning to take shape.  Another candidate move is   17.Rb1  but then Black has a nice answer in store:  Nc6 !  18.Kf1   18.Nxc6 !  isn't so good after  bxc6  19.Bxc6  Ba6+  20.Kd1  Rc8  18...Ne5  and Black has managed to shore up his previously decrepit citadel. }
17... Nd7
{ 17...a6  in order to prevent the manoeuvre Nd4-b5 is no picnic for Black either after  18.Rb1  Nc6  19.Rb6 ! }
18. Qc3 Ne5
{ Understandably, Sosonko wants to complete his development as soon as possible,  but an even more disciplined player would have continued with   18...b6 !?  19.c6  Nc5  . }
19. Nb5 Qe7
{ It seems desirable to eliminate one bishop and play   19...Nxd3  , but by doing this Black would be giving up his one piece that fulfils active functions. After  20.Qxd3  Be6  21.Nd6+  Kg7  22.h5  , White already has a decisive advantage according to Kasparov. }
20. Nd6+ Kf8
{ Now White faces an interesting choice. How should he continue attacking ? }
21. Rd1
{ The correct square for the rook, which is the only piece that hadn't been called into play yet. The move is clearly best on principle, not only because of the above factor but also because of the further enhanced king safety and the ability to develop play on the d-file.  Less stereotyped but no less strong was   21.Bc2 !  , leaving the choice of rook development for later.  After that, or even immediately, the move   21.Rb1  also comes into consideration. }
21... b6
{ Sosonko wants to undermine the strong knight on d6 and at the same time find a way to develop his bishop. }
22. Bc2
{ Kasparov is proud of this move - and rightly so. A target is placed on the forehead of the d-pawn and the d3-bishop is redeployed to another front. }
22... Ba6+ 23. Ke1 Bc4 24. Nxc4 dxc4
{ Right now it optically seems as if Black might weather the storm, but with his next move, Kasparov proves he still holds the initiative and that his bishops are still each worth a rook. }
25. Rd6
{ With the pretty threat of Rxf6. The doomed pawn on c5 lives for just long enough to facilitate this blow ! }
25... Re8 26. Bxe5
{ An excellent trade. Blacks only active piece is removed and Kasparov demonstrates that in this position diagonals have overwhelming importance. }
26... fxe5
{ After   26...Qxe5  , the answer  27.Rxf6+  Kg7  28.Rg6+  Kf8  29.Qxc4  is decisive. For example:  bxc5  30.Rxg4  with deadly threats. }
27. Qxc4 Qf7
{ After   27...Rd8  , Kasparov published the following variation in his 1981 analysis:  28.Bb3 !  Rxd6  29.cxd6  Qd7  30.Qd5 !  and Black is helpless before the flurry of threats. For instance:  Qh7  31.Qxe5  Qg7  32.Qf5+  Ke8  33.Ba4+  . }
28. Qe4
{ Kasparov gives himself another exclamation mark for this move. White's remaining bishop controls everything.  There is also   28.Qxf7+  Kxf7  29.Bg6+  Ke7  30.Bxe8  Rxe8  31.Rxh6  , reaching a winning rook endgame, but compromising on brilliance. We can say that the text move is more 'in the spirit of the position'. }
28... g3 29. fxg3
{ Black resigned, since 29. Bb3 ! and 29. Qc6 are collectively decisive threats. The final position illustrates the difference in activity between White's and Black's pieces. }
*

