[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 8. Bd3
Bb7 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. O-O c6
{ Very modest.  Here   11...c5  gives more chances of satisfactory counterplay. }
12. b4
{ This way White gets what he wants: more space on the queenside.  Also known is   12.Qb3  . }
12... Re8 13. Qb3 { 13.Rc1  is regularly played as well. } 13... Nd7 14. a4
{ Too early is   14.b5 ?!  because Black can liberate his game thanks to a tactical subtlety two moves in.  c5  15.Nxd5  Bxd5  16.Qxd5  Ne5 !  17.Qxd8  Nxf3+  18.gxf3  Raxd8  and the pawn on d4 is lost, after which the opposite-colored bishops will guarantee a completely equal game. }
14... a5 15. bxa5
{ This unconventional-looking capture, which we have already noted, is almost always going to be the best answer. }
15... Rxa5 16. Bf5 Ra6 17. Rfe1
{ It's difficult to assess where the rooks stand best.  Also suitable is   17.Rfd1 !? }
17... c5 { Yusupov sees a chance to free his game. } 18. Rab1
{ After   18.Nxd5  Bxd5  19.Qxd5  , the same trick follows:  Ne5  20.Be4  , and after   20.Qxd8  Nxf3+  21.gxf3  Rxd8  is equal.  20...Nxf3+  21.Bxf3  Qxd5  22.Bxd5  cxd4  , hardly any edge persists. }
18... g6 19. Bh3 c4 20. Qc2 Nf8 21. g3 Bc6
{ Black offered a draw here. But Georgiev saw the chances required to continue playing for a win. There is the half-open b-file which he can use to put pressure on b6, and the central moves e3-e4 and Nf3-e5 are in the air as well. }
22. Bg2 Ne6 23. h4 Nc7 { 23...Qd6  looks and sounds more normal. } 24. Kh2 Qd7
{ Of course, Black could also play   24...Bd7  with the threat of ...Bf5. Both  25.Bh3  and   25.e4  give White a slight edge. }
25. Rb4 Kg7
{ Strangely enough, this normal move gives White a substantial advantage.  Somewhat better is   25...Rea8  , although White has a convenient plus after  26.Reb1  Bxa4  27.Nxa4  Rxa4  28.Rxb6  . }
26. Reb1 Rb8
{ Yusupov doesn't show his usual tenacity.  Again   26...Rea8  made sense. The best way for White to continue then is  27.Ne5 !  After   27.Rxb6  Rxb6  28.Rxb6  Bxa4  29.Qb2 !  , White would also have had a good position.  27...Bxe5  28.dxe5  Bxa4  29.Qb2 !  and White has a plus here as well.  After   26...Ne6  , a good reaction is  27.Nd2 !?  in order to play for an advantage. White already opens the long diagonal, so that Rxb6 becomes a serious option.  Instead   27.Rxb6  Bxa4  doesn't promise White much. }
27. Ne5 Bxe5 28. dxe5 Qe7 29. f4 Qc5
{ About this position Georgiev said the following: 'Initially, I considered playing 30. Qd2 but when I delved deeper into the position, I discovered the idea Nc3-e4  (-d6)  followed by Rxc4'. Indeed a brilliant idea ! }
30. Qc1 Rba8
{ The idea of   30...b5  , which tries to get rid of the weakness, is best met by  31.h5 !  Rab6  32.axb5  Bxb5  33.hxg6  fxg6  and now the strong  34.e4  . This is supported by the tactical nuance  d4  35.Nxb5  Rxb5  36.Rxc4  Rxb1  37.Rxc5  Rxc1  38.Rxc1  and White is winning. }
31. Ne4 { Now White can show his idea. } 31... Qe7
{ Of course,   31...dxe4  doesn't help due to  32.Rxc4  Qd5  33.Rxc6  Ne6  34.Rd6  and Black can't keep things together. }
32. Nd6 { The knight now utilises this beautiful square. } 32... Bxa4 33. Rxb6
Bb3
{ Better is   33...Bd7  , but this isn't a panacea either after  34.Rxa6  Rxa6  35.Rb7  Rc6  36.Qc3 !  , winning. }
34. Rb7 R6a7 35. Rxa7 Rxa7 36. Nc8 { This material gain will be decisive. }
36... Qa3 37. Nxa7 Qxa7 38. Ra1 Qc5 39. Rb1 { 39.Qc3  was a good alternative. }
39... Ne6 40. Qc3 d4 41. exd4 Nxd4
{ Georgiev had calculated with clarity that Black's last idea has a refutation. }
42. e6 Kf8 { 42...fxe6  43.Rxb3  wins due to the same kind of double pin. } 43.
Rxb3 Nxb3 44. Qf6
{ Black admitted defeat in view of   44.Qf6  Qc7  45.Bd5  Nc5  46.e7+  Ke8   46...Qxe7  47.Qh8#  47.Bxf7+  Kd7  48.e8=Q#  . }
