1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c6 5. Bg5 Nbd7 6. e3 Qa5 7. Nd2 Bb4 8. Qc2
dxc4
{ Black trades voluntarily on c4 because White has to renounce the bishop pair to recover the pawn. }
9. Bxf6 Nxf6 10. Nxc4 Qc7
{ Still, it seems difficult for Black to open up this position. In what follows White spends a lot of time locking up the pawn structure, placing his pawns on dark squares, in order to make his own bishop better and mitigate the effect of Black's two bishops. }
11. a3 Be7 12. g3
{ White has performed an advantageous transition to a Catalan structure, which isn't treated in this book. In this structure, White never minds trading his dark-square bishop in exchange for a knight. As long as Black isn't able to free himself through c5, White usually has a small edge. }
12... O-O
{ Let's think about what happens if Black tries   12...c5  , a thematic break.  13.Bg2  Bd7   13...cxd4  14.Nb5  Qb8  15.Nxd4  is alright for White: Black can't become active for the moment.  14.Ne5  cxd4  15.exd4  and a position with an isolated pawn has arisen, in which White has active pieces. }
13. Bg2 Bd7
{ This is somewhat passive.  It was high time to push   13...c5  , for which Black won't get another chance soon due to White's next. }
14. b4 { After this move, ...c6-c5 is off the cards for the time being. } 14...
b6 15. O-O Rac8
{ Black now had a way of trying to free his game:   15...a5  . White's best response is probably  16.Ne5  axb4  17.axb4  , and now  Bxb4 ?!  can be answered nicely with  18.Nb5  Qb7  19.Bxc6  and not only has White won back his pawn, but also he will eliminate Black's bishop pair. }
16. Rfc1 Rfd8 17. Rab1 Be8 18. Ne4 Nd5 19. Ne5 Qb8 20. Qa2 Qa8
{ Black puts his queen on the line of fire of the Bg2, where it looks odd despite the intention of opening the a-file. }
21. Qb3 a6 22. Rb2 a5 23. Nd3 axb4 24. axb4 Rc7 25. Nd2 Ra7 26. Nc4 Ra1
{ The logical culmination of Black's play since move 20: using the a-file and trading pieces. }
27. Rxa1 Qxa1+ 28. Rb1 Qa6 29. Nce5 Ra8 30. Rc1 Qb5 31. Qc2 Rc8
{ Black can't touch the b4-pawn, as then there would follow:   31...Nxb4  32.Nxb4  Qxb4   32...Bxb4  doesn't work either because of  33.Bxc6  Bxc6  34.Qxc6  Qxc6  35.Rxc6  Ba5  36.h4  and White has a large advantage as Black doesn't have an active plan.  33.Bxc6  . The immediate tactics don't achieve anything as White can unravel:  Rc8  34.Qd1  Bd6  35.Rb1 !  Qc3  36.Rb3  Qa5  37.Bxe8  Rxe8   37...Bxe5 ?  is even a blunder:  38.Bd7  Rd8  39.dxe5  winning.  38.Nc4  and White has a large advantage. }
32. Ra1 Bd6 33. Ra7
{ With this maximalist move White loses control somewhat.  The correct continuation was   33.Nc4  , making the most of White's space advantage. }
33... Bxe5
{ But now   33...Nxb4 !  was possible ! After  34.Nxb4  Qxb4  , White still has to find a way to recover the pawn without losing his advantage. Note that  35.Nxc6 ??  loses a piece after  Likewise   35.Bxc6 ??  Bxe5  35...Qe1+  36.Bf1  Bxc6  . }
34. Nxe5 Nxb4 35. Qe4 Nd5 36. Bf1 Qb3 37. Qf3 Nf6 38. Ba6 Qb1+ 39. Kg2 Rd8 40.
Nxc6 { At the time control, White has recovered control of the situation. }
40... Bxc6 41. Qxc6 Qe4+
{ Black takes refuge in an endgame one pawn down. But due to the presence of a knight versus a bishop, the arising endgame is rather hard to defend, even with all the pawns of both colours so close together.  After   41...h5  , Black would also have a hard time of it. }
42. Qxe4 Nxe4 43. Rb7 g5 44. Rxb6
{ White has now reached a very favorable endgame. } 44... Kg7 45. Be2 Nf6 46.
Rb5 h6 47. h4 Rd5 48. Rc5 gxh4 49. gxh4 Rd7 50. Bf3 Ra7 51. Rc2 Re7 52. Bc6 Ra7
53. Kf3 Ra5 54. Rc3 Rf5+ 55. Kg3 Ra5 56. f4 Nd5
{ Now Kasparov makes a committal decision: he opts for a rook endgame. } 57.
Bxd5 Rxd5 58. Rc5 Rd6 59. f5 Kf6 60. Kf4 Rd8
{ Black wouldn't succeeded after another waiting move like   60...Ra6  either. For example:  61.e4  Ra4  62.e5+  Ke7  63.Rc7+  Kf8  After   63...Ke8  , there follows  64.fxe6  fxe6  65.Ke4  and the h-pawn will be lost too.  64.Rc8+  Kg7  65.f6+  Now White has a tremendously strong pawn on f6.  Kh7  66.Rd8  Rc4  67.Kg4  Ra4  68.Kh5  Ra7   68...Ra1  69.Rd7  69.Re8  followed by Re7. }
61. Rc4 Rd7 62. e4 exf5
{ Also waiting moves like   62...Ra7  won't save Black:  63.fxe6  fxe6  64.Rc6  and it's over. }
63. e5+ Ke6 64. h5 Kd5 65. Ra4 Rd8 66. Kxf5 Rg8 67. Kf6 Rg5 68. e6
{ seeing that after   68.e6  fxe6  , White will win the pawn endgame resulting after  69.Ra5+  Kxd4  70.Rxg5  hxg5  71.h6  . }
