[Black "Botvinnik, M. vs. Petrosian, T."]
[Result "*"]

{ In the world championship match between Botvinnik and Petrosian, Moscow 1963, a variation of the Queen’s Gambit was played twice, in which Black postponed ...Nf6 and had time for ...Bf5. The intuitive 7. g4 will then produce a double-edged battle. In one game White succeeded from this position, but in the other, Black did. We’ll have a look at both the games. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5
{ As was discussed in chapter 4, this  (h7-b1)  is the ideal diagonal on which to develop the light-squared bishop for Black. Therefore, it is theoretically relevant to discuss this developing move. We should also discuss White's attempt to unceremoniously boot the bishop back off this diagonal, made possible by White's omission  (thus far)  of Nf3. }
7. g4
{ This has to be done now, else Black can prevent this move with ...Nf6. } 7...
Be6
{ If the bishop tries to remain on the important diagonal with   7...Bg6  , it will lose more tempi after  8.h4 !  As we've seen in our theoretical overview, the attempt to save the tempo and take the pawn fails quite dramatically:  Bxh4 ?  9.Qb3  b6  and even now there already is a latent idea securing victory for White:  10.Rxh4 !  Qxh4  11.Nxd5  and White is winning. }
8. h3
{ In 1970 Botvinnik tried  (against Spassky)  the more aggressive approach of   8.h4 !?  but we won't be considering this right now. }
8... Nf6 9. Bd3 c5 10. Nf3 Nc6 11. Kf1 O-O 12. Kg2
{ White has walked his king to g2, carrying out a sort of artificial castling, as is normal for this structure. Black's position is extremely solid, but he lacks counterplay. }
12... cxd4
{ Later, in another world championship match between Korchnoi and Karpov, Black maintained the tension in the center and played   12...Rc8  13.Rc1  Re8  but after  14.dxc5 !  Bxc5  15.Nb5  , the champion suffered an instructive defeat. }
13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. exd4
{ White is the one in control of this position, despite the seemingly weaker position of his king. Black's problem is that there aren't any targets for him to hit. Especially in these types of positions in which he has more space and the opponent just has to wait, Botvinnik was a true master. }
14... Nd7 { 14...Rc8  seems more logical. } 15. Qc2 Nf6
{ The knight returns because Black can't permit himself to weaken his pawn structure.  After   15...h6  White however begins on the other side of the board:  16.Nb5 !  threatening Bc7, followed by Nd6 with an advantage.  And   15...g6  is not appealing at all because White can proceed intuitively with h3-h4-h5, or  (less intuitive but likely better)  16.Bh6  Re8  17.f4  with the threat of f4-f5. }
16. f3 Rc8 17. Be5 Bd6 18. Rae1
{ White can win a pawn with   18.Bxf6 ?!  , but Black would rightly consider this a cheap price for control of the dark squares.  After  Qxf6  19.Bxh7+  Kh8  20.Bd3  Qxd4  , Black is clearly better. }
18... Bxe5 19. Rxe5 g6
{ An unnecessary weakening.  Black could also have played   19...a6  a6 in order to prepare ...b7-b5.  20.g5 ?  isn't actually a threat due to  Nd7 !  and Black even gains the upper hand. }
20. Qf2 Nd7 21. Re2 Nb6 22. Rhe1 Nc4 23. Bxc4 Rxc4 24. Rd2
{ Now White has the knight versus a bad bishop. } 24... Re8 25. Re3 a6 26. b3
Rc6 27. Na4 b6 28. Nb2 a5 29. Nd3
{ The knight is showing its flexibility right now, attacking first here and then there, but White is eyeing up the e5-square for it as a permanent post. }
29... f6 30. h4 Bf7 31. Rxe8+ Bxe8 32. Qe3 Bf7 33. g5
{ In this way Black's dark squares are opened up even more. Some of his pawns might leave the board, and those that do remain will likely end up fixed on light squares, thus limiting his own bishop... }
33... Be6 34. Nf4 Bf7 35. Nd3 Be6 36. gxf6 Qxf6 37. Qg5 Qxg5+ 38. hxg5 a4
{ Even for a player like Petrosian it's very hard having to stand around watching while his opponent thinks about how to convert his advantage into a win. That's why he starts doing something. It was probably better to do nothing. }
39. bxa4 Rc4 40. a5 { 40.Nb2  also made rather a lot of sense. } 40... bxa5 41.
Nc5 Bf5 42. Kg3 { The king aims for e5. } 42... a4 43. Kf4 a3 44. Ke5 Rb4
{ Black has managed to generate a threat, i.e. ...Rb2 . Hence White takes evasive action and allows his knight to be traded, which possibility Black takes almost instantly. }
45. Nd3 Rb5 46. Kd6 Kf7 47. Kc6 Bxd3
{ Predictably seeking refuge in the rook endgame. } 48. Rxd3 Rb2
{ 48...Ra5  would probably lose too after  49.Kd6 !  followed by Rc3. } 49.
Rxa3 Rg2 50. Kxd5
{ Oddly enough,   50.Rb3 !  is stronger. Since after  Rxa2  51.Kd6 !  he'll keep the enemy king outside and it's up to him to decide when he removes d5 from the board. }
50... Rxg5+ 51. Kc6 h5 { Black has to create some counterplay quickly. } 52. d5
Rg2 53. d6 Rc2+ 54. Kd7 h4 55. f4 Rf2
{ Petrosian misses his last chance to stay in the game:   55...Kf6 !  It isn't clear whether White is actually able to force a win then, whereas after the text move he's definitely finished. }
56. Kc8 Rxf4 57. Ra7+
{ The line   57.Ra7+  Kf6  58.d7  Rc4+  59.Rc7  Rd4  60.d8=Q+  Rxd8+  61.Kxd8  g5  62.a4  is hopeless for him. }
*

