[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Botvinnik, M. vs. Petrosian, T."]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. g4 Be6 8. h3
Nf6 9. Nf3 Nbd7 10. Bd3 Nb6 11. Qc2 Nc4
{ Compared to the previous game, Black has chosen a different plan. However, this move was considered by theoreticians like Boleslavsky and Suetin to be dubious. }
12. Kf1
{ 12.Ng5  Bd7  with the idea of e3-e4 looks good for White. It is useful to provoke ...h7-h6 because White will have a target later. }
12... Nd6 13. Nd2
{ White chooses to prepare setting up the usual formation with f2-f3.   13.Ng5  Bd7  would be an idea now as well.  Of course, he could complete his king's march with   13.Kg2  . }
13... Qc8
{ This was one of the underlying ideas of Black's regrouping. By putting pressure on g4 he might be able to do something about the encirclement White intends to carry out. There is an obvious threat of ...h7-h5, which is taboo due to ...Bxh3+. }
14. Kg2 Nd7
{ 14...h5  at this moment wouldn't be such a good idea. White doesn't fear a trade on g4 as he's in a better position to take advantage of the opening h-file. }
15. f3 g6 16. Rac1
{ Perhaps a little too standard.  Tal indicated shortly afterwards that it was a good time for   16.e4 !?  , after which White has excellent prospects. }
16... Nb6 17. b3
{ Botvinnik plays very prophylactically. In this phase of the game, e3-e4 was often possible but apparently the world champion didn't feel like it.  For instance right here   17.e4 !?  was again good.  Another reasonable idea to play first is   17.Nb3  with the plan of Nc5. After  Nbc4  18.Qe2  , White can start working with e3-e4 once more. }
17... Qd7 18. Ne2 Ndc8 19. a4 a5 20. Bg3 Bd6 21. Nf4 Ne7 22. Nf1
{ Since White has refrained from the advance in the center, Black considers that he may as well take the initiative himself.  This was the last moment at which it would still have been profitable for White to play centrally with   22.e4  . }
22... h5 23. Be2 h4 24. Bh2 g5
{ Black immediately occupies considerable space on the kingside. } 25. Nd3
{ Of course,   25.Nh5  achieves little after the calm  Kd8  . } 25... Qc7
{ Well played.  Not as good is   25...Bxh2 ?!  26.Nxh2  Qc7  27.Rhf1  and White can try for f3-f4. Its important  Qg3+ ?!  28.Kh1  Qxh3 ?  doesn't work because of  29.Rg1  and the queen is trapped. }
26. Qd2
{ In order to prepare 27. Bxd6 Qxd6 28. Rc5 with an edge.  The alternative of   26.Be5 !?  would play into Black's hands:  Bxe5  27.dxe5  d4 !  28.exd4  O-O-O !  =∞  and he gets some nice squares and good play in the center. }
26... Nd7 27. Bg1
{ Botvinnik avoids the trade, but the bishop will soon retrace its footsteps.  It was again possible to play   27.e4  . After  Bxh2  28.Rxh2  f6  , Black is more comfortable, but nothing too dramatic. }
27... Ng6 28. Bh2 { An ill omen - he has no plan. } 28... Ne7 29. Bd1 b6 30.
Kg1 f6
{ Typical Petrosian: he almost never acts rashly.  Tal would have played here   30...f5 !?  (as he stated in his annotations)  when Black is better. }
31. e4 Bxh2+ 32. Qxh2
{ Perhaps White should have kept the queens on the board with   32.Rxh2  . }
32... Qxh2+ 33. Rxh2 Rd8 34. Kf2
{ The king aims for e3, but the square has, as it turns out, certain concrete drawbacks.  A better continuation was   34.Nd2  Nf8  35.Re2  , after which the position is roughly equal. }
34... Kf7
{ A little timid.  Perhaps Black could have kept an advantage with the remarkable   34...O-O !?  Now that his rooks are connected, he can think about opening the position by violent means so as to use the central files for his rooks. }
35. Ke3
{ Botvinnik doesn't have luck on his side in this game. The king is very vulnerable on e3. }
35... Rhe8 { Obviously, the rook goes to this square. } 36. Rd2 Kg7 37. Kf2
dxe4 { This is a fine moment to start attacking the center. } 38. fxe4 Nf8
{ Not only is d4 under attack, but the knight will soon be able to use e6 or g6 as jumping-off points. }
39. Ne1 Nfg6
{ Now   39...Bf7 !  would have been very strong. The bishop makes room for the knight while improving its own prospects of attacking the white center  (with a potential shift to g6 in the air)  . }
40. Ng2 Rd7 41. Bc2
{ Or   41.Nh2 !?  Red8  42.Nf3  Ne5  43.Nge1 !  with equality. } 41... Bf7
{ A little late, but White still has to watch his step. } 42. Nfe3 c5
{ In this way, Black forces the d4-pawn to give way pawn forward so that he can use the e5-square for a knight. More importantly, White's pawns will now be fixed on the wrong-coloured squares, meaning his bishop will likely never see the light of day again. }
43. d5 Ne5 { An ideal square for a knight. } 44. Rf1
{ It's not easy to keep everything together.  The best attempt was   44.Nc4  , after which Black might continue with  Nc8  with the intention of posting a knight on d6. }
44... Bg6 45. Ke1 Nc8
{ Exploiting these kinds of advantages is right up Petrosian's street. This knight goes to a new blockade square on d6. }
46. Rdf2 Rf7 47. Kd2 Nd6 { Black is clearly better by now. } 48. Nf5+ Bxf5
{ Obviously, he gives the bishop as it was the worse of the two minor pieces. }
49. exf5 c4 { In order to win, Black still needs to manage to open a-line. }
50. Rb1 b5 { Very well timed. } 51. b4
{ This doesn't help. Meanwhile trades - e.g.   51.axb5  Nxb5  52.bxc4  Nxc4+  53.Kd3  Nba3  - are also disastrous for White.  The king stands very vulnerably and Black will get an outside passed pawn. }
51... c3+ 52. Kxc3
{ After   52.Kc1  , there follows  bxa4  53.bxa5  Ra7  and Black's two passed pawns will decide the battle. }
52... Rc7+ 53. Kd2 Nec4+ 54. Kd1 Na3 { Somewhat simpler was   54...Re5  . } 55.
Rb2 Ndc4 56. Ra2 axb4 57. axb5 Nxb5
{ It is a miracle that material has been balanced so far. But as we can see, while the two armies may be equal in quantity, quality is another story entirely. Furthermore, we shouldn't forget about Black's imposing pawn on b4. It will all soon be too much for White. }
58. Ra6 Nc3+ 59. Kc1 Nxd5 60. Ba4 Rec8 61. Ne1 Nf4
{ Because after for example   61...Nf4  62.Rh2  Na3+  63.Kb2  Rc1  , what remains of the game is not worth bothering with. }
*

