[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Vladimirov, E. vs. Van der Sterren, P."]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd3 c6 8.
Nge2
{ Developing the knight to e2 is very popular. When he does this, White's future plans tend to be a little more flexible than with the steed on f3. }
8... Nbd7 9. Qc2 Re8 10. O-O-O { Vladimirov goes for opposite-side castling. }
10... Nf8 11. h3
{ The pawn storm on the kingside is getting started. So Black begins making his own preparations on the opposite wing. }
11... a5 12. g4 b5 13. Kb1 a4
{ This pawn move is essential. Black can't push ...b5-b4 through as long as a knight is still capable of paralyzing his pawn structure by going to a4. }
14. Ng3 Qa5
{ And therefore this queen move is required to give a4 extra cover. } 15. Nce2
{ A sensible move. Now the knight isn't being chased away with the loss of a tempo, and in the meantime, White attacks c6. }
15... b4
{ Black sacrifices the pawn because he would otherwise lose lots of time.  Defending it with   15...Bd7  is additionally undesirable since after  16.Nf5  ,  Bxf5  is absolutely necessary. }
16. Qxc6
{ White is correct in not backing down;  a move like   16.Qd2 ?!  would play into Black's hands. After  Ne6 !  17.Bxf6  Bxf6  and now for instance  18.f4  , the disruptive  c5 !  promises Black a significant advantage. }
16... Bd7 17. Qc1 Ne6
{ Obviously, e6 is a good square for the knight here too. } 18. Bxf6 Bxf6 19.
Qd2
{ The main difference between this position and the note to White's 16th move is that Black doesn't have the break ...c6-c5 at his disposal anymore. }
19... g6
{ Perhaps he should have continued with   19...Be7  in order to anticipate White's upcoming pawn storm. }
20. h4
{ Now that he has created a target  (i.e. Black's weakening move ...g6)  , White will try to open the h-file. }
20... Bg7 21. g5 { A strong move. He is preparing f2-f4 and only then h4-h5. }
21... Qb6
{ An understandable move. The queen wants to step off the e1-a5 diagonal because Black wants to play ...b4-b3 without trading queens. Yet after this, he'll soon be in difficulties.   21...Bf8  would enable him to put up a fight against the imminent f2-f4:  22.f4  and now Black has  Ng7  , after which his formation may hold up for just long enough. }
22. f4 Nc7
{ The game's momentum has now swung 180 degrees in just 5 moves and it is White in control. }
23. f5 { 23.h5  was strong as well. } 23... Nb5 24. Bxb5
{ The knight has to be removed, otherwise Black's counterplay could become too much. }
24... Bxb5 25. f6
{ Probably   25.h5  would have put a little more pressure on Black's position. }
25... Bf8
{ The funny thing is that Black, after this normal retreat, barely gets another chance to fight back.  But had he sacrificed the bishop after   25...Qe6 !?  , White would then have had to find something that isn't very logical, namely  26.e4 !  Taking the piece with   26.fxg7  Qxe3  would, strangely enough, give Black significant chances of tactical ideas against White's knights.  If now  26...dxe4  then after  27.fxg7  , Black lacks the same kinds of tricks. }
26. h5 Ra7 27. Nf4 Rd8 28. hxg6 fxg6
{ White is a pawn up and has a beautiful pawn on f6. But doesn't Black with his bishop pair and his apparently reasonably positioned pieces still have good chances ? This turns out to be an illusion since White has a nice, albeit unexpected, stroke that will shake the foundations of Black's king position. }
29. Nxg6 { A nice sacrifice to harass Black's king. } 29... hxg6 30. Qc2
{ Forcing ...Be8 so that the Black king can't find shelter on this square later. }
30... Be8 { 30...Kf7  31.Rh7+  Ke6  32.Qxg6  loses at once. } 31. Qh2 Kf7 32.
Qh7+ Ke6 { The king has been smoked out. } 33. f7 { A nice Novotny theme ! }
33... Bc6
{ After   33...Bxf7  , there follows  34.Rdf1  with the threat of Rf6+.  And after   33...Rxf7  34.Qxg6+  wins the queen. }
34. Qxg6+ Kd7
{ It's hard to choose for White as there are so many appealing possibilities. }
35. Rh8
{ Also possible, for instance, was   35.Qf5+  Kc7  36.g6  ;  but probably best was the calm   35.Rc1 ! }
35... Ra6
{ Not the most stubborn defense but it was too late in any case.  White also wins after something like   35...b3  36.a3  Kc7  37.Qf5  Qb8  38.g6  . }
36. Qf5+ Kc7 37. Qe5+ Kc8 38. Rc1 { Even stronger was   38.g6 ! } 38... Qb5 39.
Rxf8 { Once more a nice trick. } 39... Rxf8 40. Qe8+
{ Also good is   40.Qe6+ !  Kb8   40...Kd8  41.Qd6+  41.Qd6+  . } 40... Kc7
{ Relatively better is   40...Rxe8  41.fxe8=Q+  Kb7  but Black has no hope for salvation either after  42.Qe7+  Ka8  43.Qf8+  Kb7  44.Nf5  . }
41. Qe7+ Kb6 42. Qxf8 *

