{ Which brilliant move secures Black's victory? } 1... Be1+ 2. Kxe1
{ 54.Kf3  Bxh4  loses the knight. } 2... Qxe3+ 3. Kd1 Bb3
{ This wins the queen. } 4. Qxb3 Qxb3+
{ 56...Qxb3+  57.Ke2  Qg3  wins either the knight or the bishop. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises"]
[Black "Khalifman, A. vs. Polgar, J."]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2q3r1/1p3pk1/3R1p1p/p2Rp1r1/2P1P2Q/1P4PP/5P2/6K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ All of White’s pieces are active while Black’s aren’t working together. Considering this together with Black’s poor king safety, it seems the position is ripe for a combination. Which one, though? }
1. Rxe5 { With this beautiful move White wins an important pawn. } 1... Rd8
{ Black tries to trade the active rook on d6 in order to ease the pressure on her position, and the alternatives dont look great either:   32...a4  with the idea of attacking Whites queenside pawns comes too late:  33.Red5  axb3  34.e5  and White is winning.  On   32...Rxe5  there follows  33.Qxf6+  +-  And, of course,   32...fxe5  is met by  33.Qxh6#  . }
2. Red5 Rxd6 3. Rxd6 Rg6 4. Qf4
{ The queen stands fine here while Blacks queen and rook are poorly placed. }
4... a4
{ The following variation justifies why White can abandon his pawn on h3:   35...Qxh3  36.Rd8 !  Occupying the back rank with his rook and intending Qb8 with a strong attack on the king. For example:  Rg5  37.Qb8  Qe6  38.Rg8+  Kh7  39.Rh8+  Kg6  40.Qxb7  and Black is in a bad way. }
5. bxa4 Qxc4 6. Rd8 { The same theme as was indicated above. } 6... Qc3
{ After   37...Qxa4  38.Qb8  Qa1+  39.Kh2  f5  , White has the beautiful  40.e5  at hand, drawing the mating net closed. For example:  Rg5   40...Rc6  41.Rg8+  Kh7  42.Qf8  Qxe5  43.Qxf7+  and mate.  41.Rg8+  Kh7  42.Rh8+  Kg6  43.Qd6+  and mate follows. }
7. Kg2 Qb4 8. Ra8
{ Not only is the rook protecting pawn a4, but it also makes Qb8 possible so that the queen can take her place ahead of the rook in the battery. }
8... h5 9. Qb8
{ Whites attack has now taken on higher importance than the pawn on e4. } 9...
Qxe4+ 10. Kh2 Rg5 11. Qh8+
{ Khalifman could have forced a faster win after   42.Qg8+  Kh6  43.Qxf7  Qh7  44.Qxf6+  Rg6  45.Qf4+  Rg5  46.h4  . }
11... Kg6 12. Rg8+
{ Also here   43.Qg8+  was more effective, but it is more important to be sure of ones win, than to make it mathematically precise in an engine sense. There would follow  Kh6   43...Kf5  44.Ra5+  Ke6  45.Qe8+  44.Qxf7  . }
12... Kf5 13. Qh7+
{ 44.Qh7+  Rg6   44...Ke5  45.Re8+  45.Qxh5+  Rg5   45...Ke6  46.Re8+  46.Rxg5+  fxg5  47.Qxf7+  Ke5  48.Qe7+  and the pawn endgame is easy. }
*

