1... Rxc3
{ But now follows the amazing refutation of Blacks last move:   15...Rb8  After having calculated for a while, Black opts for this passive continuation although this most certainly cant have been his intention.  16.O-O ?!  Good enough for a nearly winning position.  However, more convincing for White would have been   16.Ne5 !  O-O  Also   16...Bxd3  will give no relief after  17.Qxd3  O-O  18.Nc6  Qc7  19.Nxe7+  Qxe7  20.Nxd5  17.Nc6  Qc7  18.Nxd5  Nxd5  19.Nxe7+  and White wins.  16...Rxb7  17.Bxf5  Nxf5  18.Bxf6  Bxf6  Whites already up a pawn but stayed alert and was able to find the following finesse by which to avoid unnecessary technical issues.  19.Ne4 !  Rb6  20.Nxf6+  Rxf6  21.Ne5  Rd6   21...O-O  isnt possible due to  22.Nd7  .  22.Qc8+  Qd8  23.Qxd8+  Rxd8  More pieces have now been traded and the pawn advantage proved to be enough to win with no further tricks.  24.Rfc1  O-O  25.Rc7  a6  26.Rac1  Rd6  27.Ra7  f6  28.Nd3  Rf7  29.Rc8+  Kg7  30.Rcc7  Rxc7  31.Rxc7+  Kf8  32.Nc5  Kg8  33.Rb7  Rc6  34.a4  Nd6  35.Ra7  Rb6  36.g4  h5  37.Rxa6  Rxa6  38.Nxa6  hxg4  39.Nc7  Nc4  40.Kg2  Kf7  41.Kg3  f5  42.Kf4  Ke7  43.Kg5  Kd6  44.Nb5+  Kc6  45.Kxg6  Nb2  46.Nc3  Nd3  47.Kxf5  Nxf2  48.Kf4 }
2. Qa4+
{ The queen on a5 is forced away from her dominant position.  Meanwhile, the most obvious White try fails:   16.b8=Q+ ?  Rc8+ !  and Black will win back the queen, having in the meantime netted a piece. }
2... Qxa4 3. b8=Q+ Rc8 { and now the twist is } 4. Bb5+
{ winning material. Following } 4... Kf8 5. Qxc8+ Bxc8 6. Bxa4
{ . White is up the exchange and a pawn, and will win. } *

