{ With his last move White has made a mistake. Black can now enact the concept he has been striving for since the opening. Which sequence of moves allows him to demonstrate this in a fine way? }
1... Bxb5
{ With this move, Black could have forced an important defender away from the White king's position. After this trade, Blacks trumps instantly become that much more relevant. White now has two possible answers: 21. Qxe4 and 21. Nxb5.  In the game, Black missed his chance and played   20...f5 ?  With this move Black loses his way.  21.Ba5 !  Soon after this move, Black got into trouble and even lost. We give the rest of the game without further comment.  Rc8  22.Bc7+  Ka8  23.Qb3  Nf3+  24.Bxf3  gxf3  25.Bg3  f4  26.Nc7+  Rxc7  27.Qxg8+  Rc8  28.Qd5  fxg3  29.hxg3  fxg2  30.b4  Bb6  31.Nf5  Bxf5  32.Qxf5  Rxc1  33.Rxc1  a6  34.Qf4  Ka7  35.Kxg2  Qxb4  36.Rc8  Bc5 ?  37.Qb8+  Kb6  38.Qc7+  Ka7  39.Qd8  Perhaps he only considered the alternative   20...Nf3+  which is indeed premature, as after  21.Nxf3  gxf3  22.Bxf3  , the knight on e4 is still hanging. }
2. Nxb5
{ , Black has a brilliant way to continue the attack.   21.Qxe4  doesnt help due to the precise  Bxe2 !  22.Nxe2  Nf3+  , winning the queen due to the pin on Whites knight after  23.gxf3  gxf3+  24.Ng3  Qxe4  .  He can play }
2... Nf3+ 3. Bxf3
{ Clearly, after   22.gxf3  , a human player can stop calculating even without finding mate. But it happens to be present, and quite photogenic too:  gxf3+  23.Kf1  Rg1+ !  24.Kxg1  Qg5+  25.Kf1  Qg2+  26.Ke1  Qxf2# }
3... gxf3 4. g3
{ . White has managed to keep the lines closed but Black has kept a pawn at f3 which supports mating motifs on the g2-square and h-file. The best way to combine these is: }
4... Qh4 { with the threat of...Qh3 and Qg2#. } 5. Qc4
{ Now the flame of combinational genius can be ignited once more: } 5... Rxg3+
6. fxg3
{ After   25.hxg3  ,  Rg8  will follow and the next sacrifice will be mate.  26.Be1  Rxg3+  27.fxg3  Bxe3+  28.Bf2  Bxf2+  29.Kf1  Qh1# }
6... Qh3
{ A little worse is   25...Rg8  on account of  26.Be1  , although Black is still winning. }
7. Qf1 f2+ { and White has to give the queen in order not to be mated. } 8.
Qxf2 { 27.Kh1  Nxg3# } 8... Nxf2 9. Kxf2 { and after for instance } 9... Qxh2+
10. Kf3 Rg8 11. Be1 Qh5+ 12. Kf2 Qf5+
{ , the game is decided. Of course, all of this wasn't easy to find, but after the text continuation, White is fully in the game again ! }
*

