{ What surprising combination enables Black to take control? } 1... Rxe4
{ An amazing exchange sacrifice. } 2. Bxe4 Ng5
{ It is important that Black has a tactical reply to } 3. f3
{ , which in this case happens to be  But also after   21.Bxg7  Bxg7  22.Bxd5  Qxd5  23.Qxd5  cxd5  ∓  , Black would have excellent prospects with two minor pieces for the rook.   21.Bxd5  This way Blacks queen and knight get to join in the attack, especially on the light squares.  Qxd5  22.Rc3   22.Rfd1  Rd8  23.Rc3  Nxh3+  would also be better for Black.  22...Rd8  23.Rd1  Nxh3+  24.Kf1  Giving Blacks queen entry,  but   24.Kh2  Nxf2  25.Bxf2  Qh5+  26.Kg2  Rxd3  27.Rdxd3  Be7  was also bad for White.  24...Qh1+  25.Ke2  Qg2 !?  Petrosian is keeping up the pressure. Whites pieces are standing rather poorly and its possible to exploit this.  Moreover,   25...Ng1+ !?  was an interesting possibility as well. After  26.Rxg1  Surely not   26.Kd2 ?  because of  c5  , winning.  26...Qxg1  27.Rxc6  Qh1  ∓  , Whites king safety is hanging in the balance although nothing has been decided yet.  26.Qe3 ?!  Whites position starts to creak a little.  The best defense appears to be   26.Qc4  .  26...Rd6  The subtle   26...Rd7 !  would have been slightly better. The difference with the game is that here c5 would remain in Blacks control.  27.Rc5 !  The only move.  Losing is   27.Bc5  because of  Rxd1  28.Kxd1  Bxc5  29.Rxc5  Nxf2+  30.Ke1  and now after the nice  Nd3+ !  31.Qxd3  Qg1+  32.Kd2  Qxc5  , Black is winning.  27...Ng1+  28.Kd2 ??  A horrible mistake that should have been punished immediately.  White had to give back the exchange:   28.Rxg1  Qxg1  and now  29.Qe4 !  keeps things together.  28...Nf3+ ?!  Petrosian gets some kind of tunnel vision around here.  The played move does indeed win, but there was an almost elementary win in   28...Rxd4+ !  29.Qxd4  Nf3+  .  29.Kc3  Re6 !  Now Black continues in a strong way,  though it should be said   29...Nxd4  30.Rxd4  Rf6 !  is at least equally strong.  30.Qd3  Nxd4  31.Qxd4  Rd6  With this forcing move Black ensures victory in a relatively simple way.  32.Qxd6  Essential is that after   32.Qg4  Rxd1  33.Qxd1  the rook on c5 is hanging:  Bxc5  32...Bxd6  33.Rxd6  White has two rooks for the queen but shell have to hand in many pawns.  Qxf2  34.Rdxc6  Qxg3+  35.Kb4  Qb8+  Here   35...g6  would make a lot of sense, as it prepares ...h6-h5. After all, the h-pawn will be the queen.  36.Rb5  Or   36.Kc3  Qf4  37.b4  f5  -+  36...Qd8  Black keeps the back rank well protected. This move is the final preparation before he starts to push pawns.  37.a4  g6  38.Rb7  Qd4+  39.Ka3  h5  40.Rc8+  Kg7  41.Rcc7  Qd6+  42.b4  Qg3+  43.Kb2  Qf2+  Black has skilfully won tempi to get the queen to this square, where she controls f7 and thus prevents any counterplay against her husband.  44.Kc3  h4  Little can be done against the coronation of the h-pawn, so White resigned. }
3... Bxe4 4. fxe4 c5
{ . Black wins back a full piece and stands clearly better. } *

