{ After which beautiful blow can Black gain the upper hand by making use of White’s poorly coordinated pieces? }
1... Rxe3
{ A surprising sacrifice that appears to work relatively often in these types of positions.  Black first ascertained that the immediate possibility   22...Bxd3  doesnt give anything special:  23.Rxd3  Rxa4  24.Qxa4  Nxb2  25.Qb3  Nxd3  26.Bxd3  and Black has only regained a previously lost pawn, with no prospect of getting more. But after the rook sacrifice, the poor coordination in Whites camp has been exposed: }
2. fxe3 Nxe3 3. Qb3
{ The queen keeps protecting the knight on a4.  Relatively better would have been   24.Qd2 !?  but after  Bxd4 !  25.Kh1  Rxa4  , Black would be winning as well. }
3... Bxd4
{ Also appealing was   24...Qg5  but after  25.Ne1  Nxd1  26.Rxd1  Bg4  , White can still put up some resistance. }
4. Kh1
{ After this what seems to be an obvious defence, White is beyond salvation.  But also after   25.Nf2  Qg5 !  26.g3  Nxd1  27.Rxd1  Bxf2+  28.Kxf2  Bxb1  29.Rxb1  Qf5+  , Black is winning. }
4... Qh4
{ Due to the unfortunate placement of Whites pieces Black can combine all of his forces on the kingside. }
5. Ndc5
{ A fun way to get mated was   26.Nc3  Ng4  27.h3  Qg3  28.hxg4  Qh4#  . } 5...
Qf2 6. Rg1 Bh3
{ In winning positions, such moves are as natural as a babys smile. } 7. Qxe3
{ This wont help him out, but nothing does, really.   28.gxh3  gets mated by  Qf3+  29.Rg2  Qxg2#  . }
7... Bxe3 8. Nd3 Qh4
{ He will be down too much material, for example:   29...Qh4  30.Nc3  Bf5  . }
