{ How would you as White try and place as much pressure as possible on Black’s position? With which move would you start and what are the ideas for bringing more units into the attack? }
1. Ng5
{ This is the right continuation indeed ! Whites not only threatening Qd3 but, perhaps after a preliminary Bxf6, also introduced the potential idea of Nxe6 followed by Bxd5. Furthermore in some lines there could be the idea of e2-e4. }
1... h6
{ This allows a combination.  After for example   17...Rcd8  , the previously mentioned idea  18.e4  is best. }
2. Bxf6 gxf6 3. Nxe6 { As promised ! } 3... Rxe6 4. Bxd5 Re8 5. Bxe6+
{ 21.e3 !?  White protects d4 and prepares Qg4.  Ne5  22.f4 ?!  This single error lets Whites advantage slip away.  Better would have been   22.Qh5 !?  For instance:  Rd8  23.Rfd1  .  With the prophylactic   22.Kg2 !  White could also have kept a large plus. The threat of f2-f4 is then very strong.  22...Qxe3+  23.Kg2  Nf7  24.Qg4+  Kh8  25.Bxe6  Qxe6 ?!  After his move, White remains in charge. Nonetheless, the position is so hard to play that mistakes are likely from both sides.  In the end, below, we see that White made the last mistake  .  Instead   25...Rxe6  26.Rc8  Re8  27.Rxe8  Qxe8  28.Rc1  would have been fair.  26.Qxe6  Rxe6  27.Rc7  Nd6  28.Kf3  Kg8  29.Rd1  Re7  30.Rc5  Re6  31.g4  Kf7  32.Rcd5  Nc8  33.Rd7+  Re7  34.a4  a5  35.Rd8  Na7  36.R1d7  Nc6  37.Rxe7+  Kxe7  38.Rd5  Ke6  39.Ke4  b6  40.f5+  Kf7  41.Rd7+  Ke8  42.Rb7  Bc5  43.Kd5  Nd8  44.Rc7  Bf2  45.Rh7  Nf7  46.Rg7  Kf8  47.Rg6  Bh4  48.Kc6  Ne5+  49.Kxb6  Nxg6  50.fxg6  Be1  51.h4  Bxh4  52.Kxa5  f5  53.gxf5  Bf2  54.Kb5  h5  55.Kc6  h4  56.f6  h3  57.Kd7  h2  58.Ke6  h1=Q }
5... Rxe6 6. Qd5 Ne5 7. Rc8 { , which is very unpleasant for Black. } *

