{ What would be a good plan for Black now that d4 has been defended as many times as he is able to attack it? With which move should he start? }
1... Bc4
{ Black is aiming for an endgame with only major pieces, as in such positions the isolated pawn will be exposed to the maximum.  After }
2. R3d2
{ 46.Nxc4  Forced.  bxc4  47.R3d2  Rd5  This is how Nimzowitsch taught us: first occupy the blocking square   d5  in front of the pawn, then continue to put further pressure on the weakness. Soon it will be lost due to the pin.  48.Qe4  e5  Carlsen needs no further preparations: the pawn can be attacked now !  49.Rc1  Rxd4  50.Rxd4  exd4  51.Rxc4  In return for the d-pawn, White has obtained one in return. Carlsen, however, has seen that the one he obtained was of better quality. This is a basic rule we know from other classical examples. In an endgame with major pieces, the player with the passed pawn already on the sixth rank  (or in this case: the third rank)  is almost winning.  d3  52.Rc1  Re7 !  The world champion can be trusted to make the most of such advantages.   52...d2 ?!  53.Rd1  Re7  would be premature because White now has a nasty trick:  54.Rxd2 !  with at least an equal game.  53.Qb4  d2  Now the push comes. The further advanced this pawn, the easier the game should be for Black. Sometimes he may not focus on the pawn itself, but rather create an attack - using the space behind and around it - on Whites king.  54.Rd1  Re2  55.Qc3  Qb6+  56.Kh2  Qg6  Mate is threatened, as we could have expected.  57.Qc8+  Kh7  58.Qg4  Qc2  And now a switch of attention back to Blacks d-pawn. His play looks very natural and easy around here, but rest assured he was expending great energy on preventing the various perpetual-check tricks.  59.f4  For White its hard to find sound moves.  Qe4   59...Qxd1  60.Qf5+  Kg8  61.Qc8+  is a draw.  60.b4  f5 !  This is the right way to proceed: he drives away the queen to a more passive square.  61.Qg3  Qc2  62.Qh3  A move like   62.h5  wont help much either because after  Qxd1  White only has one check before he must resign:  63.Qg6+  Kh8  .  62...Kh8 !  And that concludes it.  After   62...Kh8  , Qxf5+ is removed as a possibility and White cannot then expect anything more from the position. }
2... Bb3 3. Rc1 e5
{ would be very strong. The problem is White cant take the pawn with his queen, as }
4. Qxe5 { loses a piece: } 4... Re6 5. Qf4 g5 6. hxg5 hxg5
